// CH 2 — FOREST AND WILDLIFE RESOURCES
// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

const ch2_pyqs = [
  { title:"PYQ 2023", question:"How are forests classified in India? What are the problems associated with forest degradation?", answer:"Forest classification in India: (1) RESERVED FORESTS: Most valuable — under strictest government control. No rights to individuals. Comprise 53% of total forest area. (2) PROTECTED FORESTS: Some rights to local communities for grazing, fuel wood. Comprise 29% of total forest. (3) UNCLASSED FORESTS: Other forests — mostly community and private ownership. Comprise 18%. Problems of forest degradation: (1) Deforestation for agriculture, urbanisation, and industrial expansion. (2) Commercial logging for timber, pulpwood. (3) Mining — particularly open-cast mining destroys large areas. (4) Fuel wood collection by communities dependent on forests. (5) Overgrazing. (6) Forest fires. (7) Encroachment by settlers. India has lost 40% of its original forest cover. The remaining forests are often fragmented — reducing their ecological effectiveness.", year:2023, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2023", question:"What is biodiversity? Why is its conservation important?", answer:"Biodiversity refers to the variety of life on Earth at all levels: genetic diversity (within species), species diversity (number of species), and ecosystem diversity (variety of habitats). Importance of conservation: (1) ECOLOGICAL SERVICES: Biodiversity maintains ecosystem functions — pollination, seed dispersal, pest control, decomposition, nutrient cycling. Loss of any species can trigger cascading effects. (2) MEDICAL VALUE: 80% of world's medicine comes from traditional plant-based sources. New antibiotics and treatments are constantly discovered from wild organisms. (3) FOOD SECURITY: Wild relatives of crop plants provide genetic diversity essential for breeding disease-resistant varieties. (4) ECONOMIC VALUE: Ecotourism, sustainable forestry, fisheries. (5) INTRINSIC VALUE: Each species has the right to exist regardless of human utility. India is a megadiverse country — 8% of world's biodiversity on 2.4% of land.", year:2023, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2022", question:"What are the major causes of wildlife depletion in India?", answer:"Causes of wildlife depletion: (1) HABITAT LOSS: Deforestation, wetland drainage, grassland conversion — the primary cause globally. Animals need territory; fragmented habitats cannot support viable populations. (2) HUNTING AND POACHING: Despite laws, poaching continues for tiger bones (Chinese medicine), elephant ivory, rhinoceros horn, leopard skins. (3) POLLUTION: Water pollution kills fish, aquatic birds; pesticides kill raptors (DDT caused egg-shell thinning, decimating eagle and falcon populations). (4) INVASIVE SPECIES: Introduced species (water hyacinth, Lantana) outcompete native species, destroying habitats. (5) HUMAN-WILDLIFE CONFLICT: As forests shrink, animals raid crops — leading to retaliatory killing. (6) CLIMATE CHANGE: Altering habitats, disrupting migration and breeding patterns. (7) OVEREXPLOITATION: Overfishing, collection of medicinal plants beyond sustainable limits.", year:2022, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2022", question:"What is the significance of the Chipko movement in the context of forest conservation?", answer:"The Chipko movement (1970s, Uttarakhand) was a grassroots environmental movement where villagers — primarily women — literally hugged trees to prevent commercial logging. Significance: (1) SOCIAL: Led by ordinary villagers, especially women — showed that forest conservation is fundamentally a livelihood issue for the poor who depend on forests. (2) POLITICAL: Forced the Indian government to review forest policy. Led to a 15-year ban on felling green trees in the Himalayan region. (3) PHILOSOPHICAL: Introduced the principle that local communities have the right to protect their forests against state and commercial interests. (4) GLOBAL INSPIRATION: Inspired environmental movements worldwide — the 'tree-hugging' imagery became globally iconic. (5) GENDER: Highlighted women's central role in forest-based economies and conservation. (6) PRECEDENT: Contributed to later forest rights legislation (Forest Rights Act, 2006).", year:2022, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2021", question:"What are the conservation strategies adopted for protecting wildlife in India?", answer:"Conservation strategies: (1) LEGAL PROTECTION: Wildlife Protection Act (1972) — schedules animals, prohibits hunting. Forest Conservation Act (1980) — prevents diversion of forest land without central approval. (2) PROTECTED AREAS: 104 National Parks, 543 Wildlife Sanctuaries, 86 Conservation Reserves. (3) PROJECT TIGER (1973): Established tiger reserves; tiger population recovered from ~1800 to ~3000+ (though poaching remains a threat). (4) PROJECT ELEPHANT (1992): Similar programme for elephants. (5) PROJECT CROCODILE: Rescued three crocodile species from near extinction. (6) BIOSPHERE RESERVES: 18 biosphere reserves integrating conservation with human use. (7) COMMUNITY CONSERVATION: Joint Forest Management (JFM) — involving local communities in conservation. (8) CAPTIVE BREEDING AND REINTRODUCTION: For critically endangered species. (9) INTERNATIONAL CONVENTIONS: CITES (Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species).", year:2021, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2021", question:"What is the Forest Rights Act (2006) and how does it address the conflict between conservation and community rights?", answer:"The Forest Rights Act (Scheduled Tribes and Other Traditional Forest Dwellers Act) 2006 recognises and vests forest rights in forest-dwelling tribal communities who have lived in forests for generations. Key provisions: (1) Recognises tribal communities' rights to live in and use forests they have traditionally inhabited. (2) Gives rights to collect minor forest produce — fruits, nuts, honey, herbs. (3) Rights to community forest management. (4) Rights over community forest land up to 4 hectares per family. Significance for conservation-community conflict: (1) Previously, forest 'conservation' treated tribal communities as encroachers — displacing them without recognising their traditional rights. (2) The Act recognises that tribal communities have managed forests sustainably for millennia and their inclusion in conservation is necessary. (3) It shifts from top-down government-only conservation to community-based conservation — more effective and more just.", year:2021, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2020", question:"Why are community-based conservation efforts more sustainable than state-managed conservation?", answer:"Community-based conservation advantages: (1) LOCAL KNOWLEDGE: Communities possess intimate ecological knowledge of their forests — knowing seasonal changes, species behaviour, traditional management practices that took generations to develop. (2) ECONOMIC INCENTIVE: When communities benefit from forests (timber, fruits, tourism), they protect them. When conservation is purely state-imposed without community benefit, communities resist. (3) ENFORCEMENT: Local communities provide constant, 24-hour surveillance that forest departments with limited staff cannot match. (4) CULTURAL CONNECTION: Many communities have cultural and spiritual relationships with forests (sacred groves). (5) SUSTAINABILITY: Communities think in generations; government policy can change with elections. Examples: Van Panchayats in Uttarakhand, sacred groves across India, community tiger reserves. Government-only conservation often fails because: insufficient staff, corruption in forest departments, political interference.", year:2020, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2020", question:"What is the difference between national parks and wildlife sanctuaries?", answer:"NATIONAL PARKS: (1) Highest level of protection. (2) No human habitation, cultivation or grazing allowed. (3) Boundaries fixed by state legislature and cannot be changed without Parliamentary approval. (4) No rights to any community within the park. (5) Primary purpose: wildlife conservation. Examples: Corbett, Kaziranga, Gir, Sundarbans. WILDLIFE SANCTUARIES: (1) Lower level of protection than National Parks. (2) Some rights to local communities — limited grazing, fuel wood collection. (3) Boundaries can be altered by State government. (4) Human activity allowed if not harming wildlife. (5) Primary purpose: protecting wildlife, especially specific species. Examples: Bharatpur Bird Sanctuary, Sultanpur Bird Sanctuary. Biosphere Reserves are different — they are UNESCO-designated zones integrating conservation with sustainable human use.", year:2020, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2019", question:"How has colonialism affected forest resources in India?", answer:"Colonial impact on Indian forests: (1) COMMERCIALISATION: The British declared vast forests as 'Reserved Forests' under the Indian Forest Act (1878) — transferring community forests to state control for commercial timber extraction. (2) RAILWAY CONSTRUCTION: Massive timber extraction for railway sleepers (cross-ties) — tens of millions of trees felled. (3) PLANTATION MONOCULTURES: Replaced diverse natural forests with commercial plantations (teak, sal) — destroying biodiversity. (4) DESTRUCTION OF TRIBAL RIGHTS: Colonial law made tribal communities' traditional forest use 'illegal' — a conflict that persists. (5) INTRODUCTION OF INVASIVE SPECIES: Eucalyptus and other fast-growing species introduced for timber — displacing native forests. (6) OVEREXPLOITATION: During WWII, massive forest clearance for war needs. The Forest Rights Act (2006) is partly a post-colonial correction — recognising tribal rights that colonialism destroyed.", year:2019, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2019", question:"What are the factors responsible for the depletion of flora and fauna in India?", answer:"Factors for flora and fauna depletion: (1) HABITAT DESTRUCTION: Forest clearing for agriculture (particularly after independence when forest clearing was encouraged), urbanisation, dams (Narmada flooded forests), highways cutting through wildlife corridors. (2) HUNTING: Pre-independence, tiger hunting was a royal sport. Tiger population fell from 40,000 in 1900 to ~1800 in 1973 before Project Tiger. (3) OVERHARVESTING: Of timber, medicinal plants, fish — beyond natural replenishment rates. (4) POLLUTION: Industrial and agricultural chemicals killing wildlife. (5) INVASIVE SPECIES: Parthenium, water hyacinth, Lantana destroying native vegetation. (6) MINING: Open-cast mines destroying habitats irreversibly. (7) OVERGRAZING: By cattle and goats, destroying forest understory. (8) FOREST FIRES: Natural and set by farmers (jhum) or poachers. These factors are interconnected — habitat loss makes species more vulnerable to hunting, climate change and disease.", year:2019, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2023", question:"Explain India's hotspots of biodiversity. Why are they significant?", answer:"India has four recognised biodiversity hotspots: (1) EASTERN HIMALAYAS: One of the world's most biodiverse mountain ranges — home to snow leopards, red pandas, numerous orchid species. (2) WESTERN GHATS: 5,000+ species of flowering plants, 139 mammal species, 508 bird species, 179 amphibians. Home to lions (Gir, adjacent area), tigers, elephants. Severe deforestation threat. (3) INDO-BURMA REGION: Northeastern India (Assam, Manipur, Nagaland) — extraordinary biodiversity including hoolock gibbons, clouded leopards. (4) SUNDALAND: Includes Andaman and Nicobar Islands — endemic species found nowhere else. Significance: (1) Hotspots contain disproportionate global biodiversity despite small area. (2) They face disproportionate threat — hence priority conservation. (3) Conservation of hotspots protects maximum species with limited resources.", year:2023, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2022", question:"What is Joint Forest Management (JFM) and what are its objectives?", answer:"Joint Forest Management (JFM) is a programme where local communities and the Forest Department jointly manage forests. Initiated in 1988 through the National Forest Policy and expanded through government orders. Objectives: (1) Involve local communities as partners in forest conservation — recognising that conservation cannot succeed without community support. (2) Provide economic benefits to communities (share of forest produce) as incentive for protection. (3) Restore degraded forests through community participation. (4) Reduce pressure on forests by providing alternative livelihoods. (5) Utilise local ecological knowledge. Structure: Village Forest Protection Committees (VFPCs) are formed — communities protect forests in exchange for access to non-timber forest products and a share of timber revenue when the forest is commercially harvested. Problems: Communities often given less share than promised; women often excluded from decision-making; forest departments resist sharing control.", year:2022, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2021", question:"How does the Bishnoi community of Rajasthan exemplify conservation of wildlife?", answer:"The Bishnoi community of Rajasthan has practised wildlife conservation for centuries based on their religious beliefs: (1) The Bishnoi religion (founded by Jambaji in the 15th century) forbids killing animals and cutting green trees — among their 29 principles. (2) Bishnoi villages have blackbuck, chinkaras, peacocks and other wildlife living freely — protected by the community. (3) The most famous example: in 1730, Amrita Devi Bishnoi and 363 others gave their lives protecting khejri trees from being cut for a maharaja's palace — making the ultimate sacrifice for conservation. (4) Bishnoi communities have filed legal complaints against poachers (including against Bollywood star Salman Khan for blackbuck poaching). (5) Their villages are essentially informal wildlife sanctuaries. The Bishnoi example shows that spiritual and cultural values can be among the most powerful conservation tools.", year:2021, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2020", question:"What are the negative impacts of dams on forests and wildlife?", answer:"Dam impacts on forests and wildlife: (1) SUBMERGENCE: Reservoir flooding submerges forests and wildlife habitats. The Sardar Sarovar Dam (Narmada) flooded 37,000 ha of forest. (2) WILDLIFE DISPLACEMENT: Animals are displaced — often killed or unable to cross reservoir barriers. (3) FRAGMENTATION: Dams and their infrastructure (roads, canals) fragment wildlife corridors — preventing genetic exchange between populations. (4) RIVER ECOLOGY: Dams change downstream river flow, temperature, sediment load — destroying fish habitats. (5) UPSTREAM SILTATION: Creates sedimentation in the reservoir — destroying aquatic habitats. (6) INVASIVE SPECIES: Dam reservoirs often invaded by water hyacinth. (7) TRIBAL DISPLACEMENT: Thousands of tribal families displaced from forests flooded by reservoirs — severing their relationship with forest ecosystems. The costs of large dams for forests and wildlife have been systematically underestimated in project assessments.", year:2020, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2019", question:"What are invasive species and how do they threaten Indian forests and wildlife?", answer:"Invasive species are non-native organisms introduced from other regions/countries that proliferate, outcompete native species and disrupt ecosystems. Major invasive species in India: (1) LANTANA CAMARA: Thorny bush from Latin America — has invaded forest understories across India, preventing tree regeneration. Covers 40% of Nagarhole forest. (2) WATER HYACINTH (Eichhornia crassipes): From South America — chokes Indian wetlands, kills fish, prevents boat transport. Covers Loktak Lake (Manipur). (3) PARTHENIUM HYSTEROPHORUS (Congress grass): Displaces native grasses, toxic to animals. (4) EUCALYPTUS: Introduced for fast timber — depletes groundwater, provides no food/habitat for native wildlife. Threats: (1) Outcompete native species for resources. (2) Destroy habitat used by native wildlife. (3) Can trigger ecosystem collapse. (4) Cost hundreds of crores to control. Prevention is far cheaper than control.", year:2019, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
];

const ch2_easyMCQ = [
  { q:"Reserved forests in India comprise what percentage of total forest area?", opts:["29%","53%","18%","40%"], ans:1, exp:"Reserved forests — under strictest government control with no individual rights allowed — comprise about 53% of total forest area in India. Protected forests comprise 29% and unclassed forests 18%." },
  { q:"Project Tiger was launched in:", opts:["1970","1973","1980","1985"], ans:1, exp:"Project Tiger was launched in 1973 under Prime Minister Indira Gandhi to protect the rapidly declining tiger population. India's tiger count had fallen from ~40,000 in 1900 to ~1800 in 1973. The project established tiger reserves and has helped increase the population to ~3000+." },
  { q:"The Chipko movement was primarily about:", opts:["Protecting rivers","Women's rights","Protecting forests from commercial logging by hugging trees","Protecting wildlife from hunting"], ans:2, exp:"The Chipko movement (1970s, Uttarakhand) involved villagers literally embracing trees to prevent commercial logging. Led by Sunderlal Bahuguna and women like Gaura Devi. It led to a 15-year ban on felling green trees in the Himalayan region." },
  { q:"The Wildlife Protection Act was enacted in:", opts:["1970","1972","1980","1986"], ans:1, exp:"The Wildlife Protection Act was enacted in 1972. It provides the legal framework for protection of plants and animal species, prohibits hunting of scheduled species, regulates trade in wildlife products, and establishes the network of protected areas." },
  { q:"Which of these is NOT a category of protected area in India?", opts:["National Park","Wildlife Sanctuary","Biosphere Reserve","Ecological Zone"], ans:3, exp:"India's protected areas are National Parks (highest protection), Wildlife Sanctuaries, Conservation Reserves, Community Reserves, and Biosphere Reserves (UNESCO designation). 'Ecological Zone' is not a standard protected area category." },
  { q:"The Bishnoi community's conservation ethic is based on:", opts:["Government orders","Scientific training","Religious beliefs that forbid killing animals and cutting trees — one of their 29 religious principles","Economic incentives"], ans:2, exp:"Bishnois of Rajasthan follow 29 principles established by Jambaji in the 15th century, including prohibitions on killing animals and cutting green trees. Their villages have become informal wildlife sanctuaries, demonstrating that spiritual-cultural values can be powerful conservation tools." },
  { q:"The Forest Rights Act was enacted in:", opts:["1996","2000","2006","2010"], ans:2, exp:"The Scheduled Tribes and Other Traditional Forest Dwellers (Recognition of Forest Rights) Act was enacted in 2006. It recognises the rights of tribal communities to live in and use forests they have traditionally inhabited — correcting historical injustice of colonial-era forest laws." },
  { q:"India is considered a 'mega-diverse' country because:", opts:["It has the world's largest forest","It contains approximately 8% of world's biodiversity on only 2.4% of its land area","It has more species than any other country","Its forests are the oldest in the world"], ans:1, exp:"India is one of 17 'megadiverse' countries recognised by Conservation International. With only 2.4% of the world's land area, it harbours ~8% of the world's species diversity including 45,000 plant species and 91,000 animal species." },
  { q:"Water hyacinth is considered an invasive species because:", opts:["It is useful for water treatment","It originated in India","It came from South America and chokes Indian wetlands, depleting oxygen, killing fish and blocking waterways","It is eaten by all animals"], ans:2, exp:"Water hyacinth (Eichhornia crassipes) from South America is one of the world's worst invasive aquatic plants. It doubles in population every 2 weeks, forms thick mats blocking sunlight, depleting oxygen, killing fish, and preventing boat navigation. It infests most Indian wetlands." },
  { q:"Joint Forest Management involves:", opts:["Only forest department managing forests","Only tribal communities managing forests","Partnership between local communities and the Forest Department for managing forests — communities protect forests in exchange for access to forest produce","Only private companies managing forests"], ans:2, exp:"JFM was initiated in 1988. Village Forest Protection Committees are formed that jointly manage forests with the forest department. Communities get access to non-timber forest products; both parties share timber revenue. It aims to make conservation work by giving communities economic stake in forest protection." },
  { q:"The Indian Forest Act was first enacted by the British in:", opts:["1865","1878","1900","1927"], ans:1, exp:"The Indian Forest Act was enacted in 1878 under British colonial rule. It transferred vast community forests to state control, classified forests into reserved and protected categories, and made much of tribal communities' traditional forest use illegal — creating a conflict that persists." },
  { q:"Sacred groves (Dev vans) are significant because:", opts:["They are government-protected forests","They are patches of forest protected by religious and cultural taboos — preserving biodiversity and traditional ecological knowledge","They are only found in South India","They are ancient forests with no human use"], ans:1, exp:"Sacred groves are community-protected forest patches (Dev vans in Rajasthan, Orans in Rajasthan, Kovilkadu in Tamil Nadu) where cutting trees is religiously taboo. Research shows they often contain rare and endemic species that have been lost from surrounding areas — making them crucial biodiversity refuges." },
  { q:"Kaziranga National Park is famous for protection of:", opts:["Bengal Tiger","Indian Elephant","One-horned Rhinoceros","Snow Leopard"], ans:2, exp:"Kaziranga National Park in Assam is world-famous for the one-horned Indian rhinoceros (Rhinoceros unicornis). It hosts about 70% of the world's one-horned rhino population. It is also a UNESCO World Heritage Site and Tiger Reserve." },
  { q:"Forest Conservation Act (1980) aims to:", opts:["Promote commercial logging","Prevent diversion of forest land for non-forest purposes without prior central government approval","Allow unrestricted mining in forests","Promote plantation monocultures"], ans:1, exp:"The Forest Conservation Act 1980 requires prior approval of the Central Government before any state government or authority can divert forest land to non-forest use (mining, dams, agriculture, roads). It was enacted to check rapid deforestation for development projects." },
  { q:"Project Elephant was launched in:", opts:["1973","1988","1992","2000"], ans:2, exp:"Project Elephant was launched in 1992 — modelled on Project Tiger — to protect Indian elephants, their habitats and migration corridors. It provides financial and technical support to states with elephant populations and works to reduce human-elephant conflict." },
];

const ch2_mediumMCQ = [
  { q:"How does habitat fragmentation threaten wildlife survival?", opts:["Fragmentation has no effect on wildlife","It only affects large animals","Fragmentation divides continuous habitat into isolated patches — too small to support viable breeding populations of large animals like tigers. Animals attempting to cross fragmented landscapes (between forest patches) are killed on roads/railways. Inbreeding in small isolated populations reduces genetic diversity and disease resistance","Fragmentation only matters for plant species"], ans:2, exp:"Habitat fragmentation is one of the greatest threats to wildlife. A tiger needs 50-100 sq km territory; if forests are fragmented into smaller patches, no patch can support a tiger. Even if individual patches are protected, animals cannot disperse to new territories, find mates or recolonise after local extinction. Wildlife corridors (connecting forest patches) are therefore as important as the patches themselves." },
  { q:"Why is the human-wildlife conflict intensifying in India?", opts:["Wildlife populations are always declining","Conflict was always high","As forest cover shrinks due to encroachment, mining, and development, wildlife is forced into agricultural areas — raiding crops, killing livestock, occasionally attacking humans. As wildlife populations recover (tigers, elephants) in protected areas, pressure on surrounding areas increases. The conflict is fundamentally about space competition between growing human and wildlife populations","Conflict only involves tigers"], ans:2, exp:"Human-wildlife conflict is a pressing conservation-development challenge. Elephant raids on crops in Assam and Jharkhand; tiger attacks in Sundarbans; leopard attacks near urban areas — these are increasing because: (1) Wildlife habitats are shrinking. (2) Human settlements are expanding into former wildlife areas. (3) Some wildlife populations are recovering. Managing this conflict through compensation schemes, early warning systems, and maintaining wildlife corridors is essential for both human safety and conservation." },
  { q:"What is the significance of wildlife corridors for conservation?", opts:["Corridors are tourist pathways","Corridors have no conservation value","Wildlife corridors are strips of habitat connecting isolated protected areas — allowing animals to move between areas for breeding, recolonisation after local extinction, and seasonal migration. Without corridors, protected areas become ecological islands — populations decline through inbreeding, local extinctions are permanent rather than temporary. The Terai Arc Landscape and Central Indian Tiger Landscape are important corridor systems in India","Corridors only matter for elephants"], ans:2, exp:"Wildlife corridors are increasingly recognised as essential supplements to protected areas. The classic example: the Western Ghats has several tiger populations in different reserves. Without corridors connecting these reserves, tigers cannot exchange genetic material — each population becomes an isolated 'island' subject to inbreeding depression. Studies show tiger populations connected by corridors have higher genetic diversity and are more resilient. Elephant corridors in the Nilgiris Biosphere Reserve have been mapped and are being protected — but face constant development pressure." },
  { q:"Why has the conservation approach shifted from 'fortress conservation' to 'community conservation'?", opts:["Governments ran out of money for protected areas","Local communities always supported fortress conservation","Fortress conservation — strictly protected areas with no human access — failed in practice: (1) Did not address the root cause (habitat loss outside protected areas). (2) Created conflict by displacing communities with legitimate rights. (3) Produced 'islands' of protection surrounded by hostile communities. Community conservation recognises that long-term conservation requires local community support — which comes only when communities have rights and benefits, not just restrictions","Community conservation is less effective than fortress conservation"], ans:2, exp:"The shift from fortress to community conservation is one of the most important developments in conservation thinking. Evidence from India and globally: fortress-style conservation (strict exclusion of people from protected areas) has sometimes succeeded for specific species (Project Tiger populations in core areas) but failed for landscapes as a whole, as surrounding areas are degraded and communities excluded from forests become hostile to conservation. Community-based conservation (Van Panchayats in Uttarakhand, community forest management in Orissa) has shown that communities with rights and benefits often protect forests better than government departments." },
  { q:"How does climate change affect forest biodiversity?", opts:["Climate change only affects humans not forests","Forests are immune to climate change","Climate change alters temperature and rainfall patterns, shifting habitat zones — species adapted to specific conditions cannot always move fast enough. (1) Himalayan species are moving to higher altitudes but some face extinction when they run out of mountain. (2) Monsoon changes affect forest composition. (3) Increased forest fires. (4) Phenological mismatch — flowering, fruiting, and migration timing disrupted. (5) Range shifts alter species interactions (predator-prey, pollinator-plant)","Climate change will increase forest biodiversity"], ans:2, exp:"Climate change is now recognised as a major threat to forest biodiversity, compounding habitat loss and hunting. Studies in the Western Ghats show some species' ranges are already shifting upward. For mountain species (snow leopard, red panda), upward shifts eventually run out of mountain — creating 'mountain islands' with no escape. Coral reefs are the marine equivalent — bleaching from ocean warming has destroyed 50% of Great Barrier Reef since 1995. The Indian Himalayan forests face particular risk as both temperature and precipitation patterns change." },
  { q:"What is the Integrated Protected Area System (IPAS) and what does it seek to achieve?", opts:["A single large national park for all India","A system of interconnected protected areas (national parks, wildlife sanctuaries, biosphere reserves, corridors) designed to protect viable populations of all Indian wildlife across their natural ranges","A database of protected areas","Only for tiger conservation"], ans:1, exp:"IPAS recognises that no single protected area, however large, can protect all wildlife. India's network includes 104 national parks, 543 wildlife sanctuaries, 86 conservation reserves — covering about 5% of India's geographical area. But this is insufficient unless these areas are (1) internally well managed, (2) buffered by community forests, and (3) connected by wildlife corridors. The wildlife census shows 53 tiger reserves — but tigers exist only in viable numbers where all three conditions are met." },
  { q:"How did colonial forest policy in India harm both tribal communities and forest ecosystems?", opts:["Colonial forest policy benefited everyone","Colonial policy improved forests","Colonial forest policy (Indian Forest Acts 1865, 1878, 1927) transferred community forests to state control — primarily for commercial timber extraction for railways and the military. This: (1) Destroyed tribal communities' rights over forests they had sustainably managed for millennia. (2) Introduced commercial logging that harvested forests far beyond sustainable rates. (3) Replaced diverse natural forests with plantation monocultures. (4) Made traditional practices (jhum, fire management) illegal. The conflict between forest-dwelling communities and the Forest Department is a direct legacy of colonialism","Tribal communities supported colonial forest policy"], ans:2, exp:"Colonial forest policy created lasting damage to both communities and ecosystems. The 1878 Forest Act declared vast forests 'reserved' — tribal communities who had lived in these forests for generations became 'encroachers' overnight. The new forest managers (British-trained forest officers) had commercial extraction as their primary mandate, not conservation. The result: both the extractive commercial model AND the criminalisation of traditional practices degraded forests. The Forest Rights Act (2006) is the belated partial correction of this colonial damage." },
  { q:"What is the IUCN Red List and how does it guide conservation priorities?", opts:["A list of invasive species","A list of all species in India","The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species classifies species by extinction risk: Extinct, Extinct in the Wild, Critically Endangered, Endangered, Vulnerable, Near Threatened, Least Concern. It guides conservation by identifying which species need immediate intervention","A government document for hunting licenses"], ans:2, exp:"The IUCN Red List is the world's most comprehensive database of species conservation status. In India: Critically Endangered species include the Great Indian Bustard (fewer than 150 remaining), Gangetic River Dolphin, Indian Wild Ass. The Red List guides: where to establish protected areas, which species need captive breeding, where to direct conservation funding. Without this systematic assessment, conservation resources would be allocated arbitrarily." },
  { q:"Why is the depletion of medicinal plants a major concern in India?", opts:["Medicinal plants are not important in modern medicine","India has unlimited medicinal plants","India is one of the world's great centres of traditional medicinal plant knowledge — Ayurveda, Unani, Siddha systems use thousands of plant species. Over-harvesting of wild medicinal plants (Neem, Ashwagandha, Sarpagandha, Kuth) has depleted many species. The biodiversity loss threatens: (1) Traditional medicine systems used by millions. (2) Future pharmaceutical discovery — many modern drugs originated from plants. (3) Tribal knowledge systems that are disappearing with plants","Medicinal plants can be replaced by synthetic chemicals"], ans:2, exp:"India's medicinal plant wealth is extraordinary — over 8,000 species used medicinally in traditional systems. But demand from the domestic and international herbal medicine industry has caused over-harvesting of wild populations. Species like Aconitum (used in Ayurveda), Picrorhiza kurroa (picrorrhiza), and Nardostachys jatamansi are declining. The problem is compounded by: (1) Most collection from wild rather than cultivated sources. (2) Lack of regulation on collection. (3) Disappearance of forest habitats. Given that ~25% of modern pharmaceuticals are derived from plants, this is not just a traditional medicine issue." },
  { q:"What is 'bioprospecting' and why is it controversial in the context of Indian forest biodiversity?", opts:["It is the same as conservation","It is completely beneficial","Bioprospecting is the systematic search for biological material (plants, animals, microbes) with potential commercial value (pharmaceuticals, cosmetics, agriculture). Controversy: (1) Foreign companies bioprospect Indian forests without compensating India or tribal communities who hold traditional knowledge. (2) This traditional knowledge (which plants heal which diseases) is often the starting point for discovery. (3) Companies then patent products derived from Indian biodiversity. (4) The Convention on Biological Diversity (1992) established the principle of 'Access and Benefit Sharing' — but enforcement is weak. Examples: Turmeric patent controversy, Neem patents by US companies","Bioprospecting is banned in India"], ans:2, exp:"The turmeric case is iconic: a US company patented the wound-healing use of turmeric — knowledge known to every Indian grandmother for centuries. India challenged the patent in the US Patent Office, producing ancient texts showing prior knowledge, and won. Neem patents were similarly challenged. This 'biopiracy' — appropriating traditional knowledge without compensation — prompted India to push for stronger benefit-sharing rules in international negotiations. The Nagoya Protocol (2010) established legally binding access and benefit-sharing requirements, partially addressing this issue." },
  { q:"Why is the conservation of mangroves particularly important for both biodiversity and human communities?", opts:["Mangroves have no special value","Mangroves only matter for fish","Mangroves — coastal forests in tidal zones — provide multiple services: (1) Biodiversity: nursery habitat for 80% of world's fish species; home to birds, reptiles, mammals. (2) Coastal protection: mangrove roots dissipate wave energy — the 2004 tsunami caused far less damage in areas with intact mangroves than cleared areas. (3) Carbon storage: among the highest per-hectare carbon stores of any ecosystem. (4) Livelihoods: fishing communities depend on mangrove fish nurseries. India's Sundarbans (world's largest mangrove) is under severe threat from sea level rise, development and tiger-human conflict","Mangroves are only in the Sundarbans"], ans:2, exp:"Mangroves are among the most valuable ecosystems per hectare on Earth, yet among the most threatened. India has lost 40% of mangroves in the last 50 years. The 2004 tsunami provided devastating evidence of mangroves' protective value — villages behind intact mangroves suffered far less damage. The Sundarbans supports tigers, Irrawaddy dolphins, fishing communities, and one of the world's largest carbon stores — but sea level rise is submerging islands at an increasing rate. Pichavaram mangroves in Tamil Nadu protected coastal villages in 2004." },
  { q:"What is the significance of the Sundarbans as both a biodiversity hotspot and a human settlement area?", opts:["Sundarbans is only for tigers","Humans don't live in Sundarbans","Sundarbans — the world's largest mangrove delta (India+Bangladesh) — is a UN World Heritage Site and Tiger Reserve. It hosts: Bengal tigers, Irrawaddy dolphins, estuarine crocodiles, 260+ bird species. But also millions of people living in fishing and agricultural communities. This creates: (1) Human-tiger conflict (tigers kill fishers/honey collectors). (2) Deforestation pressure from land hunger. (3) Sea level rise threatening both humans and wildlife. Managing a World Heritage Site that is also home to millions of poor people requires integrating conservation with human development — one of the most complex conservation challenges in the world","Sundarbans has no people"], ans:2, exp:"The Sundarbans represents the ultimate conservation-development paradox. Its tiger population (~96 tigers) is iconic. But 4 million people — some of the world's poorest — also depend on it for fish, honey, timber, and agricultural land. Tigers kill fishers and honey collectors; communities sometimes retaliate. Sea level rise (3mm/year) is submerging islands, forcing communities deeper into the forest and into tiger territory. There is no easy solution — managing this requires addressing poverty while protecting one of the world's most threatened ecosystems." },
  { q:"How does the loss of apex predators (like tigers) affect entire forest ecosystems?", opts:["Apex predators have no ecosystem role","Only prey species are affected by predator loss","Apex predators regulate entire ecosystems through trophic cascades: tigers control deer/wild boar populations; without tigers, deer/boar increase, overgraze forest understory, preventing tree regeneration. This is called a 'trophic cascade'. Evidence: (1) Where tigers have been extirpated, deer populations explode, forests are degraded. (2) Reintroduction of wolves to Yellowstone National Park changed river course by controlling deer movement (Yellowstone Effect). Apex predators are 'keystone species' — disproportionately important to ecosystem health relative to their numbers","Only in Africa, not India"], ans:2, exp:"The concept of trophic cascades revolutionised conservation biology. Removing an apex predator doesn't just reduce predator numbers — it cascades through the entire ecosystem. India example: areas without tigers or leopards show deer/boar population explosions that overgraze forest floor, prevent seedling establishment, and gradually change forest composition. This is why Project Tiger focused not just on tigers but on protecting entire ecosystems ('tiger landscapes') including prey and habitat." },
  { q:"ASSERTION: The Forest Rights Act (2006) represents a fundamental shift in India's approach to forest conservation.\nREASON: It shifts from treating tribal forest dwellers as encroachers to recognising their traditional rights — implicitly acknowledging that their presence can be compatible with conservation.", opts:["Both A and R true; R explains why the shift is fundamental","Both true but unconnected","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"Both correct. Colonial forest policy (and post-independence policy that continued it) treated tribal communities as threats to forests — displacing them to 'save' forests. This paradox: (1) Tribal communities had managed these forests sustainably for millennia. (2) Forest loss accelerated after they were excluded. (3) Forest departments often failed to prevent poaching and encroachment by others while prosecuting tribal communities for traditional practices. The FRA's fundamental shift: traditional forest dwellers are rights-holders, not encroachers — and their inclusion in management is necessary for effective conservation." },
];

const ch2_hardMCQ = [
  { q:"ASSERTION: India's biodiversity hotspots are disproportionately threatened by development pressures.\nREASON: Hotspots typically coincide with regions of high human population density and agricultural potential — creating direct competition between biodiversity conservation and human development needs.", opts:["Both A and R true; R explains why hotspots are threatened despite their value","Both true but unconnected","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"Both correct. This is the fundamental challenge of biodiversity conservation in developing countries. The Western Ghats: high biodiversity hotspot but also home to 50 million people, extensive tea, coffee and spice plantations, major hydroelectric potential. The Eastern Himalayas: biodiversity hotspot but also home to tea gardens, tribal communities, military infrastructure. Conservation is hardest precisely where it is most needed — where biodiversity and human need overlap most intensely." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: A new highway is proposed through a wildlife corridor connecting two tiger reserves. The project authority argues it will create development; conservationists argue it will destroy a critical corridor. Evaluate using resource management principles.", opts:["The highway should always be built","The highway should never be built","The decision requires: (1) Environmental Impact Assessment that quantifies corridor value (genetic exchange between populations, long-term viability of both reserves). (2) Analysis of whether alternative routes exist that avoid the corridor. (3) If corridor crossing is unavoidable, engineering solutions (wildlife underpasses, overpasses, speed limits) should be mandated. (4) Cost-benefit analysis must include ecological services value of tigers and intact corridors. Standard economic calculations systematically undervalue biodiversity — the highway's development benefits would likely be overvalued and corridor's conservation value undervalued. Precautionary principle: loss of a wildlife corridor may be irreversible","Engineers always know best"], ans:2, exp:"This scenario is playing out across India — NH7 through Pench-Kanha corridor, NH44 through Northeast India's corridors. The evidence shows: wildlife underpasses and overpasses significantly reduce corridor mortality when properly designed and maintained. India's National Tiger Conservation Authority has developed guidelines requiring wildlife passages in highways crossing wildlife corridors. But enforcement is variable. The deeper issue: economic development benefits are tangible and immediate; biodiversity corridor benefits are diffuse and long-term — creating systematic bias in decisions." },
  { q:"EXTRACT-BASED: 'Extinction is forever.' What are the implications of this statement for how we should approach biodiversity conservation?", opts:["Extinction is reversible with modern science","Extinction doesn't matter since new species evolve","Extinction's irreversibility justifies: (1) Applying the precautionary principle — if uncertain about a species' importance, err on the side of conservation. (2) Prioritising prevention over remediation — a species extinct is lost from all future options (medical, agricultural, ecological). (3) Recognising special obligations toward critically endangered species even at economic cost. (4) Challenging 'de-extinction' technologies as false security — bringing back a species doesn't restore the ecosystem it evolved within. The temporal irreversibility of extinction makes it qualitatively different from other environmental impacts that can potentially be remediated","Extinction is not a major concern"], ans:2, exp:"'Extinction is forever' encapsulates why biodiversity loss is treated differently from other environmental problems. A polluted river can be cleaned; a felled tree can regrow; but an extinct species is gone from the evolutionary tree. This irreversibility justifies: (1) Extreme precaution — the 'safe minimum standard' approach that says never allow extinction unless the cost of prevention is intolerably high. (2) Long-term thinking — a species with no known current use may be the source of tomorrow's cancer cure. (3) Ethical consideration of species' intrinsic rights independent of human utility." },
  { q:"ASSERTION: Community-based conservation in India has been more successful where communities have legally recognised rights over forests.\nREASON: Legal rights give communities security to invest in long-term conservation — without rights, communities have no incentive to conserve forests they could lose access to at any time.", opts:["Both A and R true; R correctly explains the importance of legal security for conservation","Both true but unconnected","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"Both correct. This is supported by evidence from Van Panchayats (Uttarakhand), community forests in Orissa, and the Chhattisgarh Joint Forest Management experience. Where communities have legal rights: they invest in protection (posting guards, preventing illegal cutting), they benefit from improved forests (more fruit, better water, more timber), and they have legal standing to challenge encroachment. Without rights: communities are insecure about future access, have no incentive to conserve, and may themselves degrade forests before someone else does — a forest version of the tragedy of the commons." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: How does the 'willingness to pay' for wildlife tourism reveal both the value and the limits of market-based conservation?", opts:["Wildlife tourism has no conservation value","Market mechanisms perfectly value biodiversity","Wildlife tourism shows: (1) Value — tourists' willingness to pay to see tigers demonstrates that intact ecosystems have substantial economic value. Jim Corbett National Park generates ₹300+ crore annually. (2) Limits — (a) Most biodiversity has no tourism value (insects, soil organisms, but essential for ecosystems). (b) Concentrates conservation resources in iconic megafauna (tigers) at expense of less charismatic species and habitats. (c) Tourism revenue rarely reaches communities adequately. (d) Heavy tourist pressure itself damages wildlife. Market value captures only a fraction of total biodiversity value","Wildlife tourism is harmful"], ans:2, exp:"Wildlife tourism demonstrates the potential of market mechanisms while revealing their limitations. Kerala's elephant tourism; Rajasthan's tiger tourism; Kaziranga's rhino tourism — all generate revenue that justifies conservation economically. But: (1) Soil bacteria, beetles, and fungi are worth far more to ecosystems than tigers but have no tourism value. (2) Local fishing communities' livelihoods (which depend on biodiversity) are often undervalued relative to tourist experiences. (3) 'Charismatic megafauna' dominates conservation funding while less visible but ecologically crucial species are ignored. Market mechanisms need to be supplemented by non-market valuation." },
  { q:"How does the decline of vultures in India illustrate the cascading effects of biodiversity loss?", opts:["Vultures are not important","Vulture decline only affects other vultures","Vulture populations in India declined 97-99% in the 1990s-2000s from diclofenac (veterinary drug that poisoned vultures that ate treated cattle carcasses). Effects: (1) Loss of scavenging service — 10,000+ kg of dead cattle per year per vulture. (2) Increase in feral dog populations feeding on carcasses — carrying rabies. (3) Increase in wild pig populations. (4) Anthrax outbreaks from inadequately decomposed carcasses. (5) Human rabies deaths. Economic study estimated vulture services worth $34 billion/year in South Asia. This case shows how a single species' loss can cascade through entire ecosystems and human health systems","Vultures can be replaced by other animals"], ans:2, exp:"The Indian vulture crisis is one of the most dramatic and instructive biodiversity loss events in recent history. Three species (white-backed, long-billed, slender-billed vultures) declined 99.9% in 15 years — the fastest decline ever recorded for a bird. The cause: diclofenac in cattle carcasses (banned for veterinary use in 2006 but still available). The consequences: as vultures disappeared, carcass piles attracted millions of feral dogs, rabies transmission to humans increased. Economic analysis showed that vultures' free scavenging service was worth more than the entire revenue of Indian wildlife tourism. Captive breeding programmes have produced some recovery." },
  { q:"ASSERTION: The extinction of large mammals like elephants and tigers would fundamentally change Indian forest ecosystems.\nREASON: These species are 'ecosystem engineers' — their feeding, movement and behaviour patterns shape habitat structure for hundreds of other species.", opts:["Both A and R true; R correctly identifies the mechanism","Both true but unconnected","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"Both correct. Elephants as ecosystem engineers: (1) Create waterholes used by dozens of other species. (2) Disperse seeds of large-fruited trees that cannot be dispersed by smaller animals — some trees may go extinct without elephants. (3) Create forest clearings that increase edge habitat diversity. (4) Their dung is used by hundreds of dung beetle species. Tigers: control prey distribution and density, preventing overgrazing of forest floor. The loss of these 'megafauna' would trigger cascading changes affecting hundreds of dependent species — an 'empty forest syndrome' where the forest physically remains but its ecological function is fundamentally altered." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: Why is ex-situ conservation (zoos, seed banks) insufficient as a conservation strategy, though valuable as a supplement?", opts:["Ex-situ conservation is the best strategy","Ex-situ conservation is completely useless","Ex-situ limitations: (1) Cannot maintain evolutionary processes (natural selection, co-evolution with other species). (2) Animals lose behaviours needed for wild survival. (3) Genetic diversity in captive populations too small — inbreeding. (4) Species in zoos are absent from ecological roles (vultures not scavenging, tigers not regulating prey). (5) Seed banks preserve genetic material but not ecological relationships. (6) Astronomically expensive to maintain all threatened species ex-situ. Value as supplement: (1) Insurance against extinction while in-situ habitat is restored. (2) Captive breeding for reintroduction. (3) Genetic resource preservation. (4) Research and education. Strategy: use ex-situ to buy time while fixing the in-situ causes of decline","Zoos are better than national parks"], ans:2, exp:"The reintroduction of Indian Cheetah to Kuno National Park (from Namibia, 2022) illustrates both the value and limits of ex-situ conservation. The cheetahs were carefully chosen for genetic diversity, managed in captivity, and prepared for release. But success requires that the ecological conditions for their survival (sufficient prey, secure territory, absence of major conflict with humans) exist in-situ. Captive management can preserve individual animals but cannot restore the ecological relationships they need. The Arabian Oryx, California Condor, and Arabian Scimitar Oryx were saved from extinction by captive breeding and successful reintroduction — showing ex-situ's value when combined with habitat restoration." },
  { q:"EXTRACT: 'Protected areas are the cornerstone of biodiversity conservation but they are not enough.' What additional strategies does the evidence suggest are necessary?", opts:["Protected areas are completely sufficient","Additional strategies are irrelevant","Evidence shows protected areas need to be supplemented by: (1) Wildlife corridors connecting isolated protected areas. (2) Buffer zones where limited human use is compatible with biodiversity. (3) Biodiversity-friendly land use in agricultural and urban landscapes (agroforestry, shade-grown coffee). (4) Reducing pressures on forests outside protected areas (reducing demand for timber, reducing agricultural expansion). (5) Community conservation areas providing continuity of habitat. (6) Climate change adaptation strategies. Without these supplements, protected areas become isolated islands that cannot maintain viable populations of wide-ranging species like tigers over multiple generations","All wildlife should be in protected areas"], ans:2, exp:"Conservation biology has moved beyond the 'island biogeography' model of protected areas since the 1980s. Landmark studies showed that isolated protected areas of insufficient size inevitably lose species over time — even without any obvious threat. India's Project Tiger data shows: reserves with good surrounding forests and corridors maintained higher tiger numbers than isolated reserves of equal size. The landscape approach to conservation — managing entire landscapes including human-dominated areas for biodiversity — is now the dominant paradigm, supplementing rather than replacing protected area management." },
  { q:"ASSERTION: Biodiversity loss in India is inseparable from questions of social justice.\nREASON: The communities most dependent on biodiversity (tribal, fishing, pastoral) bear the highest costs of biodiversity loss and conservation restrictions, while the benefits (ecosystem services, ecotourism revenue) accrue primarily to urban populations and the state.", opts:["Both A and R true; R correctly explains the justice dimension","Both true but unconnected","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"Both correct. This justice analysis is fundamental to understanding why conservation fails without addressing equity. Adivasi communities displaced from Tiger Reserves: lost livelihoods, homes and cultural identity while tigers are preserved for global audiences. Fishing communities in coastal conservation areas: excluded from traditional fishing grounds while coastal resorts are allowed. Pastoral communities: restricted from traditional grazing routes through wildlife corridors. The costs of conservation are concentrated on poor, marginalised communities while benefits are diffuse and largely captured by urban/global populations and the state. Addressing this inequity is not just morally necessary but practically essential for conservation success." },
  { q:"How does the concept of 'ecosystem services' change the economic argument for biodiversity conservation?", opts:["Ecosystem services are not relevant to economics","Ecosystem services make conservation more expensive","Ecosystem services valuation (Costanza et al., TEEB) shows that intact ecosystems provide free services worth far more than their commercial exploitation: (1) Water purification by wetlands. (2) Carbon storage by forests. (3) Pollination by insects. (4) Soil formation by soil organisms. (5) Flood protection by coastal ecosystems. When these services are quantified (Costanza estimated global ecosystem services at $33-$145 trillion/year), conservation becomes economically rational — destroying an ecosystem for short-term development gains destroys far more economic value in services than is gained. This changes the economic argument from 'conservation vs development' to 'conservation IS development'","Ecosystem services are only for developed countries"], ans:2, exp:"The TEEB (The Economics of Ecosystems and Biodiversity) study was a watershed in conservation economics. It showed that ecosystems provide services worth multiples of their extractive value. Classic example: mangrove destruction for shrimp farming generates ~$1,200/ha in shrimp revenue but destroys ~$10,000/ha in fishery support, coastal protection, and carbon storage services. The calculation doesn't make shrimp farming irrational in a market that doesn't price ecosystem services — but it makes it irrational from a social welfare perspective. Incorporating ecosystem services into national accounting (India has a Natural Capital Accounting project) is needed to correct this market failure." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: In the 1970s-80s, Project Tiger displaced tribal communities from core tiger reserve areas. Some tiger populations have recovered; tribal communities have suffered. How should this trade-off be assessed?", opts:["Tiger recovery justifies all displacement","Tribal rights always outweigh tiger conservation","The trade-off requires moral and practical evaluation: (1) Morally: displacing the poorest communities for conservation benefiting global audiences is a serious injustice — particularly given these communities often lived in forests sustainably for millennia. (2) Practically: studies show tiger reserves WITH community participation have done as well or better than those with forcible exclusion. (3) The correct lesson: tiger conservation was necessary (tigers were on verge of extinction) but forcible displacement was both unjust and often unnecessary. Integrated approaches (community rights + conservation goals) can achieve both. Post-2006 Forest Rights Act has begun addressing the injustice","All conservation areas should be abandoned"], ans:2, exp:"India's Project Tiger experience contains both genuine achievement and genuine injustice. Tiger populations have recovered significantly (1800 in 1973 to 3000+ today) — a conservation success. But 200,000+ tribal people were displaced from tiger reserves without adequate compensation or rehabilitation. Research by wildlife biologists (including those who designed Project Tiger) now acknowledges that forcible exclusion was often unnecessary and counterproductive — communities who knew the forests and had a stake in them could have contributed to tiger recovery. The FRA attempts to address the historical injustice while maintaining conservation — but implementation is contested." },
];


