const ch3_pyqs = [
  { title:"PYW 2023", question:"Why is water considered a scarce resource in India despite being a country with many rivers and high rainfall?", answer:"Water scarcity in India despite surface water wealth: (1) UNEVEN DISTRIBUTION: Over 75% of annual rainfall falls in 3-4 monsoon months, causing floods then drought. Geographically: Northeast India receives 11,000mm; Rajasthan gets <300mm. (2) OVEREXPLOITATION: Groundwater is being extracted faster than it recharges — Punjab, Haryana, Rajasthan face severe depletion. (3) POLLUTION: Industrial effluents, agricultural chemicals, untreated sewage make much surface water unusable — Ganga, Yamuna, several rivers are severely polluted. (4) LACK OF STORAGE: Without storage, monsoon water flows to sea. India's per-capita storage capacity is very low compared to developed countries. (5) POPULATION GROWTH: More people need more water — per capita availability has fallen from 5177 m³ in 1951 to ~1545 m³ today. (6) INEFFICIENT USE: 80% of water use in agriculture, much wasted through flood irrigation. (7) CLIMATE CHANGE: Disrupting rainfall patterns.", year:2023, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2023", question:"What are multi-purpose river projects? What benefits do they provide and what problems have they caused?", answer:"Multi-purpose river projects (dams) serve multiple objectives: irrigation, hydroelectricity, flood control, domestic/industrial water supply, navigation, fisheries, recreation. Benefits: (1) Provided irrigation water enabling the Green Revolution in Punjab and Haryana. (2) Hydroelectricity — Bhakra-Nangal, Hirakud provide large amounts of power. (3) Flood control — reduced devastating floods in Damodar valley. (4) Domestic water supply to millions. Problems: (1) DISPLACEMENT: Tens of millions of people displaced, mostly tribal, without adequate rehabilitation. Sardar Sarovar displaced 320,000+. (2) SUBMERGENCE: Forests, wildlife, agricultural land, cultural heritage sites flooded. (3) SEDIMENTATION: Dams fill with silt, reducing life span and storage capacity. (4) WATERLOGGING AND SALINISATION: Excessive irrigation causes water table to rise and salts to accumulate — making land infertile. (5) SEISMIC IMPACT: Large reservoirs can trigger earthquakes. (6) FISHERIES: Blocks fish migration routes. (7) DOWNSTREAM EFFECTS: Changes river hydrology, reduces sediment to delta.", year:2023, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2022", question:"What are the main causes of water pollution in India? What are the effects on human health and the environment?", answer:"Causes of water pollution: (1) INDUSTRIAL EFFLUENTS: Toxic chemicals, heavy metals, hot water from factories discharged into rivers. Ganga, Yamuna receive effluents from tanneries, textile mills, paper mills. (2) AGRICULTURAL CHEMICALS: Pesticides and fertiliser runoff from farms — nitrates cause eutrophication. (3) UNTREATED SEWAGE: Only ~30% of India's sewage is treated — rest flows directly into water bodies. (4) SOLID WASTE DUMPING: Garbage in rivers and lakes. (5) RELIGIOUS PRACTICES: Immersion of idols, ash, dead bodies in rivers. Health effects: (1) Waterborne diseases — cholera, typhoid, diarrhoea kill hundreds of thousands annually. (2) Heavy metal poisoning — mercury, arsenic, lead cause neurological damage, cancer. (3) Nitrate poisoning (blue baby syndrome) from contaminated groundwater. Environmental effects: (1) Aquatic ecosystem destruction — fish, amphibians die. (2) Eutrophication — algal blooms deplete oxygen. (3) Bioaccumulation of toxins up the food chain.", year:2022, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2022", question:"Describe the traditional methods of water conservation practised in different parts of India.", answer:"Traditional water conservation methods vary by region: (1) KHADINS (Rajasthan): Earthen embankments that retain monsoon runoff for winter agriculture in semi-arid conditions. (2) JOHADS (Rajasthan/Haryana): Village ponds that recharge groundwater and provide water for humans and animals. Rajendra Singh revived hundreds of johads in Alwar district. (3) STEP WELLS (Rajasthan, Gujarat): Intricately designed wells with steps descending to water level — architectural marvels and practical water storage. (4) TANKS (South India): Stone-built or earthen reservoirs — some 2000 years old. Irrigated vast areas of Deccan and Tamil Nadu. (5) KULS (Himachal Pradesh): Diversion channels from glaciers and streams to agricultural fields. (6) BAMBOO DRIP IRRIGATION (Meghalaya): Ingenious gravity-fed bamboo pipe systems up to 200m long. (7) INUNDATION CHANNELS (Bihar): Using seasonal flood water for irrigation. (8) AHAR-PYNE (Bihar): Ancient irrigation system — ahar (reservoir) + pyne (canal).", year:2022, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2021", question:"What is rainwater harvesting and why is it important?", answer:"Rainwater harvesting is the collection and storage of rainwater for later use — either from rooftop run-off or by directing surface runoff into storage structures. Methods: (1) Rooftop harvesting — rain collected from roof, filtered, stored in underground tank. (2) Check dams — small dams across streams to hold water and allow percolation. (3) Percolation tanks — allow water to seep into ground, recharging groundwater. (4) Contour bunds — earthen ridges along contour lines that hold water and allow percolation. Importance: (1) Augments water supply in water-scarce areas. (2) Recharges depleted groundwater — crucial as over-extraction has lowered water tables severely. (3) Reduces flooding — holds water that would otherwise run off. (4) Reduces dependency on government water supply. (5) Low-cost, decentralised water management. (6) Communities that harvest rainwater become self-sufficient — Rajendra Singh's Alwar revival transformed a water-scarce region. In Chennai, rooftop rainwater harvesting has been made mandatory.", year:2021, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2021", question:"How has irrigation transformed Indian agriculture? What are its negative consequences?", answer:"Irrigation's transformation of Indian agriculture: (1) Enabled year-round cultivation in areas with dry winters or summers. (2) Made the Green Revolution possible — high-yielding varieties need reliable water. (3) Reduced dependence on monsoon — areas like Punjab and Haryana became food secure. (4) Increased crop diversity — fruits, vegetables, flowers now grown in semi-arid regions. (5) Multiple cropping — two to three crops per year instead of one. Negative consequences: (1) WATERLOGGING: Over-irrigation raises water table — roots suffocate. Large areas of Punjab have waterlogged soils. (2) SALINISATION: When water evaporates in hot dry areas, salts concentrate — soil becomes infertile. Major problem in irrigated parts of Rajasthan, UP, AP. (3) GROUNDWATER DEPLETION: Tube well irrigation far exceeds recharge rates in many states. (4) MICRONUTRIENT DEPLETION: Intensive irrigation-based farming depletes trace elements. (5) SUBSIDISED ELECTRICITY: Pump irrigation subsidised — encouraging overuse. (6) WATER CONFLICTS: Inter-state disputes over river water (Kaveri, Krishna, Narmada).", year:2021, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2020", question:"What is the Narmada Bachao Andolan (NBA)? What issues does it raise about large dam projects?", answer:"The Narmada Bachao Andolan (Save Narmada Movement) is a social movement led by Medha Patkar against the construction of large dams on the Narmada River, particularly the Sardar Sarovar Dam (Gujarat). Issues raised: (1) DISPLACEMENT: 320,000+ people displaced — mostly tribal Adivasis, farmers, fishermen — without adequate resettlement. (2) SUBMERGENCE: Forests, wildlife, agricultural land, archaeological sites flooded. (3) REHABILITATION: Displaced people resettled on inferior dry land without water. (4) DEMOCRATIC PROCESS: Local communities not consulted on a project affecting their homes. (5) COST-BENEFIT: Did not account for social and environmental costs; benefits primarily for urban Gujarat. (6) ALTERNATIVES: Could the same water and power objectives have been achieved through smaller, decentralised solutions? The NBA forced a global reconsideration of large dam projects — the World Commission on Dams (2000) concluded that many large dams' costs exceeded benefits.", year:2020, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2020", question:"Why is the Ganga river highly polluted? What are the consequences?", answer:"Ganga pollution causes: (1) UNTREATED SEWAGE: Cities from Haridwar to Kolkata discharge millions of litres of untreated sewage daily. (2) INDUSTRIAL EFFLUENTS: Kanpur's tanneries discharge chromium and other heavy metals; textile mills, sugar mills, paper mills discharge toxic waste. (3) AGRICULTURAL RUNOFF: Pesticides and fertilisers from Ganga plains' agriculture. (4) RELIGIOUS PRACTICES: Immersion of idols, ash, dead bodies. (5) OPEN DEFECATION: In villages along the river — though Swachh Bharat has reduced this. Consequences: (1) Biological oxygen demand (BOD) extremely high — few fish can survive. (2) Coliform bacteria (from sewage) make water dangerous for bathing and drinking. (3) Heavy metals in water — causing health problems in riverine communities. (4) Loss of biodiversity — Gangetic river dolphins, turtles, Mahseer fish severely declined. Despite Ganga Action Plan (1986) spending ₹4000+ crore, pollution levels remain extremely high — showing that technical solutions alone cannot solve what is fundamentally a governance and political economy problem.", year:2020, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2019", question:"What is 'water harvesting' as practised in semi-arid Rajasthan? How effective is it?", answer:"Water harvesting in Rajasthan: (1) KHADINS: Earthen embankments across drainage channels in semi-arid areas. Rain water and runoff retained behind embankment; silt settles, enriching soil; winter crops grown on silted area. Some khadins are 500+ years old. (2) JOHADS: Village ponds — simple earthen embankments to collect rainwater. Used for domestic, livestock and agricultural purposes. Also recharge groundwater. (3) BAWDIS/STEP WELLS: Deep wells with descending steps — architectural and practical water storage. (4) NADI: Small earthen storage reservoirs. Effectiveness: Rajendra Singh's work in Alwar district (Tarun Bharat Sangh NGO) restored 8,600 johads between 1985-2007. Results: (1) Five rivers that had run dry flowed again — groundwater recharge. (2) Crop yields increased dramatically. (3) Villages that had faced drinking water scarcity became self-sufficient. (4) Wildlife returned to watered areas. The programme won Singh the Stockholm Water Prize ('Water Gandhi').", year:2019, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2019", question:"What is the difference between surface water and groundwater? What are the problems associated with groundwater depletion?", answer:"SURFACE WATER: Water in rivers, lakes, reservoirs, ponds — visible and accessible. India receives 4000 billion cubic metres of rain annually; only ~1000 bcm is utilisable surface water. GROUNDWATER: Water stored in underground aquifers — replenished slowly by percolation of rainwater. India has about 400 bcm of utilisable groundwater. Problems of groundwater depletion: (1) UNSUSTAINABLE EXTRACTION: Punjab extracts 170% of annual recharge — the water table drops 0.5-1m annually. (2) QUALITY DEGRADATION: As water table drops, older, often saline/contaminated water is accessed; arsenic from rock strata is released. (3) SUBSIDENCE: Ground sinks as underground water is removed — buildings crack, land collapses. (4) SALTWATER INTRUSION: In coastal areas, when freshwater groundwater is depleted, seawater enters aquifers. (5) COST INCREASE: Deeper wells and more powerful pumps needed — unaffordable for poor farmers. (6) ABANDONMENT: Some areas in Rajasthan have no usable groundwater at accessible depths.", year:2019, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2023", question:"What are inter-state water disputes in India? Describe one major example.", answer:"Inter-state water disputes arise when rivers flow through multiple states that share the water. India has several major disputes. KAVERI WATER DISPUTE: The Kaveri (Cauvery) River flows through Karnataka and Tamil Nadu. The dispute: Karnataka (upper riparian state) built the Krishnaraja Sagar and Kabini dams, reducing water flow to Tamil Nadu (lower riparian state). Tamil Nadu farmers argue they have historical rights to Kaveri water for paddy cultivation. The dispute began in the British era and has continued post-independence. Key events: (1) Kaveri Water Disputes Tribunal established in 1990. (2) Tribunal gave interim orders for Karnataka to release water. (3) 2018: Supreme Court reduced Karnataka's allocation and increased Tamil Nadu's. (4) Riots in both states when water releases were ordered. The dispute illustrates: (1) Water is a development resource whose allocation determines farmers' livelihoods. (2) River water cannot be divided without political conflict. (3) National integration requires shared water governance frameworks.", year:2023, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2022", question:"How can water use efficiency in agriculture be improved?", answer:"Agricultural water use efficiency improvements: (1) DRIP IRRIGATION: Delivers water directly to plant roots — reduces water use by 30-60% vs flood irrigation. Israel uses drip irrigation extensively; India's adoption is growing. (2) SPRINKLER IRRIGATION: More uniform water distribution than flood irrigation; reduces water use by 30-40%. (3) CROP SELECTION: Shifting to drought-tolerant or less water-intensive crops in water-scarce areas (millets, pulses instead of paddy in Punjab). (4) SOIL MOISTURE MONITORING: Irrigating only when soil moisture falls below threshold — avoiding overwatering. (5) CANAL LINING: Reduces water seepage loss in distribution canals. (6) PRICING WATER: Eliminating irrigation subsidies to encourage efficient use. (7) PADDY TRANSPLANTING: Reducing the flooded-field period (SRI method — System of Rice Intensification). (8) TRADITIONAL METHODS: Reviving local water harvesting to reduce dependence on canal/groundwater irrigation.", year:2022, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2021", question:"What is the hydrological cycle and why is it important for understanding water as a resource?", answer:"The hydrological (water) cycle describes the continuous circulation of water through the Earth's systems: (1) EVAPORATION: Solar energy converts water from oceans, lakes, rivers to water vapour. (2) TRANSPIRATION: Plants release water vapour. Combined = evapotranspiration. (3) CONDENSATION: Water vapour cools and forms clouds. (4) PRECIPITATION: Rain, snow, sleet fall. (5) RUNOFF: Water flows into rivers and ultimately back to oceans. (6) PERCOLATION: Some rainfall enters the ground, recharging aquifers. (7) GROUNDWATER FLOW: Moves slowly toward rivers and sea. Importance for resource management: (1) Shows water is finite and renewable — the same water is continuously recycled. (2) Explains why overextraction of groundwater disrupts the cycle. (3) Shows why deforestation reduces rainfall (less transpiration = less moisture in atmosphere). (4) Climate change disrupts the cycle — altering when and where precipitation falls. (5) Contamination at any point affects the whole cycle.", year:2021, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2020", question:"Explain the concept of 'virtual water'. How does it relate to water scarcity?", answer:"'Virtual water' (Allan, 1993) is the water embedded in food and other products — the water used to produce them. Examples: 1 kg of wheat requires ~1000 litres; 1 kg of beef requires ~15,000 litres; 1 cup of coffee requires ~200 litres; 1 smartphone requires ~13,000 litres. Relevance to water scarcity: (1) Water-scarce countries (Israel, Jordan) import virtual water by importing food rather than growing it domestically — saving their scarce water. (2) Countries like India export virtual water through agricultural exports (cotton, rice) — effectively exporting their scarce water. (3) India is one of the world's largest virtual water exporters despite widespread water scarcity. (4) Virtual water trade can help water-scarce countries if they import water-intensive goods rather than producing them domestically. Policy implication: Water-scarce regions should shift from water-intensive crops (paddy, cotton) to less water-intensive crops (millets, pulses, fruits).", year:2020, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2019", question:"What measures has India taken to manage its water resources at the national level?", answer:"National water management measures: (1) NATIONAL WATER POLICY (1987, revised 2002, 2012): Establishes priorities for water use — domestic first, then agriculture, industry, environment. (2) NATIONAL RIVER LINKING PROJECT: Proposed linking of 37 rivers to transfer water from surplus to deficit regions — controversial. (3) JAL SHAKTI MINISTRY: Merged water resources and drinking water ministries. (4) NATIONAL WATER MISSION: One of India's National Action Plan on Climate Change missions — targets 20% water use efficiency improvement. (5) ATAL BHUJAL YOJANA: Programme for sustainable groundwater management in overexploited areas. (6) JALSHAKTI ABHIYAN: Community water conservation campaign. (7) JAL JEEVAN MISSION: Providing piped water to all rural households by 2024. (8) INTERSTATE WATER DISPUTES TRIBUNALS: For adjudicating disputes between states. (9) CENTRAL WATER COMMISSION: National body for water resource development.", year:2019, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
];

const ch3_easyMCQ = [
  { q:"What percentage of Earth's water is fresh water?", opts:["50%","25%","About 2.7%","10%"], ans:2, exp:"About 97.3% of Earth's water is in oceans (salt water). Only about 2.7% is fresh water — and of this, most is locked in glaciers and ice caps. Only about 0.006% of all Earth's water is readily accessible as surface fresh water in rivers and lakes." },
  { q:"Which Indian river is most polluted according to CPCB?", opts:["Brahmaputra","Kaveri","Yamuna","Narmada"], ans:2, exp:"The Yamuna, particularly around Delhi, is consistently rated as one of the most polluted rivers in India by the Central Pollution Control Board. Delhi contributes 80% of the Yamuna's pollution through untreated sewage, while accounting for only a 22km stretch of the river." },
  { q:"Bhakra-Nangal dam is built on which river?", opts:["Ganga","Yamuna","Sutlej","Beas"], ans:2, exp:"Bhakra-Nangal dam — India's largest multi-purpose dam — is built on the Sutlej River in Himachal Pradesh/Punjab. The Bhakra dam (226m tall) and the Nangal barrage together form the Bhakra-Nangal project, providing irrigation to Punjab, Haryana and Rajasthan." },
  { q:"Drip irrigation is most effective for:", opts:["Flood irrigation in large flat fields","Saving water by delivering it directly to plant roots — reduces water use by 30-60%","Irrigating rice paddies","Large-scale wheat cultivation"], ans:1, exp:"Drip irrigation (also called micro-irrigation or trickle irrigation) delivers water drop by drop directly to plant roots through a network of pipes and emitters. It reduces evaporation and runoff — saving 30-60% water compared to conventional flood irrigation. Particularly valuable for horticultural crops." },
  { q:"The Narmada Bachao Andolan was led by:", opts:["Anna Hazare","Rajendra Singh","Medha Patkar","Sunderlal Bahuguna"], ans:2, exp:"Medha Patkar, a social activist, led the Narmada Bachao Andolan (Save Narmada Movement) against large dam construction on the Narmada — particularly the Sardar Sarovar Dam. The movement raised fundamental questions about displacement, rehabilitation, and the true costs of large dam projects." },
  { q:"Rajendra Singh won the Stockholm Water Prize for:", opts:["Building large dams","Designing desalination plants","Reviving traditional johad water harvesting systems in Rajasthan — restoring dried rivers and water-scarce villages","Developing drip irrigation technology"], ans:2, exp:"Rajendra Singh ('Water Gandhi') led the Tarun Bharat Sangh in restoring 8,600+ johads (traditional water harvesting ponds) in Rajasthan's Alwar district. This revived five rivers that had dried up, restored groundwater, and transformed water-scarce villages — winning him the Stockholm Water Prize (2015)." },
  { q:"Waterlogging in irrigated areas is caused by:", opts:["Too little irrigation","Excess irrigation raising the water table until roots are submerged in water","Drip irrigation","Rainwater harvesting"], ans:1, exp:"Waterlogging occurs when over-irrigation raises the water table until agricultural soils become saturated with water. Roots need oxygen from air-filled pores — when submerged in water, crops suffocate and die. Major problem in canal-irrigated areas of Punjab, Haryana and Rajasthan." },
  { q:"What is salinisation?", opts:["Adding salt to water for purification","The accumulation of salts in irrigated soils as water evaporates — making soil infertile","Salt water flooding coastal areas","The process of making sea water drinkable"], ans:1, exp:"Salinisation occurs in irrigated areas where water evaporates in hot weather, leaving behind dissolved salts. Over years, salt concentrations build up to levels toxic to crops. Major problem in arid irrigated areas (Rajasthan, parts of UP and AP). Affected soils appear white and support no vegetation." },
  { q:"The largest consumer of water in India is:", opts:["Domestic use","Industrial use","Agriculture (80%+)","Power generation"], ans:2, exp:"Agriculture accounts for over 80% of India's water use — mostly for irrigation. Domestic use is about 8% and industrial use about 5%. This is why improving agricultural water use efficiency (through drip irrigation, crop selection, pricing) is the key to India's water security." },
  { q:"Bamboo drip irrigation is a traditional water conservation method used in:", opts:["Rajasthan","Meghalaya","Kerala","Punjab"], ans:1, exp:"Bamboo drip irrigation is an ingenious traditional system used in Meghalaya (Northeast India) by the Jaintia and Khasi tribes. Bamboo pipes of different diameters and angles carry water from streams over distances up to 200 metres, delivering it drop by drop to terraced fields — a traditional drip irrigation system." },
  { q:"The Hirakud dam is built on which river?", opts:["Godavari","Mahanadi","Krishna","Chambal"], ans:1, exp:"Hirakud dam is built on the Mahanadi River in Odisha. It is one of the longest dams in the world (4.8 km). It provides irrigation, flood control and hydroelectricity. Its reservoir submerged large areas, displacing many communities." },
  { q:"What is eutrophication?", opts:["Purification of water","Excessive algal growth in water bodies due to nutrient pollution — depletes oxygen, kills fish","The natural cycle of water","A method of water treatment"], ans:1, exp:"Eutrophication is the enrichment of water bodies with nutrients (mainly nitrates and phosphates from agricultural runoff and sewage). This triggers algal blooms that block sunlight, then die and decompose — depleting oxygen and killing fish. Most Indian lakes and many rivers suffer from eutrophication." },
  { q:"India's first large dam is considered to be:", opts:["Bhakra-Nangal","Hirakud","Mettur Dam (Stanley Reservoir) on Kaveri","Sardar Sarovar"], ans:2, exp:"The Mettur Dam (officially Stanley Reservoir) on the Kaveri River in Tamil Nadu, built in 1934, is often cited as India's first major dam. It provided irrigation to the delta regions of Tamil Nadu and is the largest dam in Tamil Nadu." },
  { q:"The World Commission on Dams (2000) concluded:", opts:["All dams should be built","Dams are perfect solutions to water problems","Many large dams' social and environmental costs exceeded their benefits — and displaced communities were systematically undercompensated","Dams are not needed for development"], ans:2, exp:"The World Commission on Dams (established after international controversy about large dam impacts) published its report in 2000. It concluded that while dams had contributed to human development, the social and environmental costs — particularly displacement without adequate rehabilitation — had been unacceptably high, and many projects had not met their stated objectives." },
  { q:"Step wells (bawdis/vavs) found in Gujarat and Rajasthan served to:", opts:["Provide only drinking water","Store only monsoon runoff","Provide access to groundwater through descending steps — serving as water supply, social space and architectural monuments in arid regions","They were purely decorative"], ans:2, exp:"Step wells (bawdis, vavs) are extraordinary architectural and functional structures — wells with multiple descending staircases allowing access to water at different levels. They served as: water supply throughout dry seasons, public gathering spaces, places of rest for travellers, and sometimes religious sites. Rani ki Vav (Patan, Gujarat) is a UNESCO World Heritage Site." },
];

const ch3_mediumMCQ = [
  { q:"Why does India's high annual rainfall not translate into high water security?", opts:["Indian rainfall is not reliable","India's rainfall is seasonal — 75%+ in 3-4 monsoon months — and geographically concentrated. Without storage infrastructure (dams, check dams, groundwater recharge), most water flows to sea. Additionally, maldistribution within the country (11,000mm in Cherrapunji vs 100mm in Jaisalmer) means national averages are misleading","India doesn't have high rainfall","Storage technology doesn't exist"], ans:1, exp:"The key to understanding India's water paradox: total annual precipitation is enormous (~4000 billion cubic metres) but utilisation is low because: (1) Most falls in 100 hours of heavy rain concentrated in 4 months. (2) Without storage, monsoon runoff is wasted. (3) Storage capacity per capita is very low — India's per-capita storage is 220 cubic metres vs USA's 6150 cm. (4) Geographically, the rainfall is concentrated in Eastern Himalaya and Western Ghats while large dry areas exist." },
  { q:"How does the construction of large dams affect downstream ecosystems?", opts:["Dams have no downstream effects","Dams improve downstream river quality","Dams fundamentally change downstream rivers: (1) Reduce flow — less water for downstream agriculture and ecosystems. (2) Trap sediment — rivers below dams become 'hungry' for sediment, causing channel erosion and delta shrinkage. (3) Change temperature — cold, oxygen-poor water from reservoir depths affects fish. (4) Block fish migration — hilsa, salmon and other migratory fish cannot pass dams. (5) Reduce flood pulses that maintain floodplain ecosystems. The Farakka Barrage has contributed to the shrinking of the Ganga delta in Bangladesh","Dams only affect the reservoir area"], ans:2, exp:"Downstream effects of dams are among the most underappreciated environmental impacts. The Colorado River in the USA — dammed by Hoover Dam and others — now rarely reaches the sea. The Indus Delta in Pakistan has shrunk dramatically as Tarbela Dam traps sediment and water. India: Farakka Barrage on Ganga has reduced freshwater flow to the Ganga delta in Bangladesh — causing salinisation of agricultural land and threatening the Sundarbans. These downstream transboundary effects are rarely fully accounted for in dam cost-benefit analyses." },
  { q:"What is the 'tragedy of the groundwater commons' in India?", opts:["Groundwater has no owners so no one uses it","The government controls all groundwater","Each farmer has incentive to extract as much groundwater as possible (since neighbours will pump it if they don't), leading to collective over-extraction that depletes the aquifer for everyone. Individual rationality produces collective irrationality — the classic commons tragedy. Punjab's water table falls 0.5-1m annually as farmers collectively extract far more than recharge","Groundwater is evenly distributed"], ans:2, exp:"India's groundwater crisis is a classic commons problem. Groundwater beneath a farm also underlies neighbouring farms — there's no boundary. If you conserve your use, your neighbour pumps that same water. Therefore each farmer's rational strategy is to pump as much as possible. Result: India extracts 25% of the world's groundwater despite having 18% of its population. Punjab, Haryana, Rajasthan and coastal Gujarat have critically depleted aquifers. Solving this requires collective governance — regulating what individuals cannot individually restrain themselves from doing." },
  { q:"Why is river interlinking in India controversial?", opts:["It is technically impossible","Only engineers disagree about river interlinking","River interlinking (connecting 37 rivers to transfer water from surplus to deficit regions) is controversial because: (1) Ecological concerns — altering river hydrology could destroy ecosystems. (2) Political concerns — donor states (Brahmaputra basin, Kerala) resist giving their water to recipient states. (3) Financial concerns — estimated cost ₹5-11 lakh crore. (4) Better alternatives exist — water conservation, efficiency improvement, local harvesting. (5) Hydrological disputes — are there really 'surplus' rivers? Brahmaputra flows through sensitive geopolitical terrain. (6) Displacement — canal construction would displace communities","All scientists support river interlinking"], ans:2, exp:"The National River Linking Project (NRLP) has been discussed for decades but remains unimplemented due to massive obstacles. Technical objections: what is 'surplus'? Rivers described as having surplus water are those that flood during monsoons — transferring this water requires timing that may not align with deficit areas' needs. Political objections: Kerala, which would give water to Tamil Nadu under some proposals, strongly objects. Ecological objections: environmentalists argue that 'surplus' rivers' flood pulses are essential for downstream ecosystems." },
  { q:"How does urbanisation affect water resources?", opts:["Urbanisation improves water management","Urban areas have unlimited water","Urbanisation (1) increases impervious surface area — concrete replaces soil, reducing percolation and groundwater recharge. (2) Increases water demand per capita — urban industrial/domestic use is much higher than rural. (3) Generates large quantities of wastewater that often enters rivers untreated. (4) Destroys urban wetlands that act as natural water storage and treatment. (5) Changes local weather — urban heat islands modify rainfall patterns. (6) Creates urban flood risk as natural drainage is replaced by concrete","Urbanisation reduces water demand"], ans:2, exp:"The hydrological impact of urbanisation is profound. A natural area typically infiltrates 40% of rain — recharging groundwater. A fully paved urban area infiltrates only 5% — 95% becomes runoff, causing floods then droughts. Mumbai: heavy monsoon flooding followed by summer water scarcity — both partly the result of replacing permeable surfaces with concrete. Urban wetland destruction (Bangalore's 85% lake loss; Hyderabad's Hussain Sagar) has worsened floods and reduced water storage." },
  { q:"What is the 'Jal Jeevan Mission' and what challenge does it address?", opts:["It is an irrigation programme","It is a flood control programme","Jal Jeevan Mission (launched 2019) aims to provide piped drinking water connections to every rural household by 2024 — addressing the problem that 80% of India's rural households lacked piped water, relying on distant hand pumps, wells, or open water sources that are often contaminated","It is only for cities"], ans:2, exp:"Jal Jeevan Mission is one of India's largest infrastructure programmes. Context: millions of women and girls spent hours daily collecting water — reducing time for education and economic activity. Contaminated water sources caused 37.7 million Indians to fall ill annually from waterborne diseases. The mission targets household piped connections for all 192 million rural households. Progress has been rapid — from 16% coverage in 2019 to 60%+ by 2022 — but ensuring water quality and sustained supply remains challenging." },
  { q:"Why is pricing water a contentious but potentially necessary policy?", opts:["Water pricing is purely technical","Pricing water always leads to conservation","Water pricing is contentious because: (1) Water is a human right — the poor must not be denied it due to inability to pay. (2) Agricultural water pricing (removal of subsidies) would force many marginal farmers out of business. (3) Political economy — any pricing of currently free water faces intense political resistance. BUT pricing can be necessary because: (1) Subsidised water (especially for irrigation) encourages waste — farmers use far more than optimal. (2) Without pricing, infrastructure deteriorates (no revenue for maintenance). (3) Progressive pricing (low prices for basic needs, higher for excess use) can conserve while protecting poor users. India's water-intensive crops (paddy in Punjab) are partly the result of subsidised electricity for pumping","Pricing has no conservation effect"], ans:2, exp:"The water pricing debate is fundamentally about competing values: efficiency vs equity, conservation vs agricultural development. Punjab's rice cultivation is an outstanding example: Punjab farmers use rice paddy because: (1) MSP (Minimum Support Price) guarantees a market. (2) Free electricity for pump irrigation has no cost consequence. (3) Green Revolution technology is optimised for paddy. Remove subsidised electricity, and rational farmers would shift to less water-intensive crops — dramatically reducing Punjab's groundwater crisis. But this would reduce farm incomes in the short run. The political economy of agricultural subsidies makes the reform extremely difficult." },
  { q:"What is the 'virtual water' concept and why is it significant for Indian water policy?", opts:["Virtual water is water that doesn't exist","India should stop all agricultural exports","Virtual water (embedded water in products) is significant for India because: India exports millions of tonnes of rice, cotton, sugar — all very water-intensive crops. This represents enormous quantities of virtual water exported from a water-scarce country. Policy implication: (1) India should consider water scarcity when deciding which crops to produce and export. (2) Exporting water-intensive crops from water-scarce states worsens groundwater depletion. (3) Trade patterns should reflect water endowment — water-scarce countries should import water-intensive goods, not export them","Virtual water is only relevant for oil-exporting countries"], ans:2, exp:"India is one of the world's largest virtual water exporters — a paradox given its severe water scarcity. India exports ~100 billion cubic metres of virtual water annually, mainly through agricultural products. Rice is the biggest virtual water export: 1 kg of rice requires 1,650 litres of water. India is the world's largest rice exporter. Punjab, which grows much of this rice, has a falling water table — effectively mining fossil groundwater to subsidise international consumers. The policy recommendation: reform agricultural incentives to encourage less water-intensive crops in water-scarce areas." },
  { q:"How does arsenic contamination of groundwater in West Bengal and Bihar occur?", opts:["From industrial pollution","From agricultural chemicals","Arsenic occurs naturally in certain geological formations (Holocene sediments of the Ganga delta). When groundwater is heavily pumped, arsenic is released from the rocks into the water. Over-extraction of groundwater accelerates arsenic release. Drinking arsenic-contaminated water causes: skin lesions, neuropathy, and cancers. 50 million people in West Bengal and Bihar are exposed to arsenic above safe limits — one of the world's largest environmental health crises","Arsenic is added deliberately"], ans:2, exp:"The West Bengal arsenic crisis is one of the most severe environmental health disasters in history, described by the WHO as 'the largest mass poisoning of a population in history'. It emerged in the 1980s when tube wells were sunk for drinking water (replacing potentially bacterially-contaminated surface water). The arsenic occurs naturally in Holocene alluvial sediments and is released under reducing conditions when organic matter decomposes. The problem is geogenic (natural) but accelerated by over-extraction. Treatment options exist (arsenic removal filters) but coverage remains incomplete." },
  { q:"What are the implications of climate change for India's monsoon and water resources?", opts:["Climate change will improve India's water situation","India's monsoon will become completely reliable","Climate change projections for India: (1) More intense but shorter monsoon events — more flooding, less percolation to groundwater. (2) Longer dry spells between rain events. (3) Himalayan glacier retreat — short-term increase in glacier melt-fed rivers, long-term reduction. (4) Sea level rise threatening coastal aquifers and delta agriculture. (5) Increased evapotranspiration in warmer temperatures reducing soil moisture. Net effect: more water stress — particularly for rainfed agriculture and communities dependent on glacial rivers. Adaptation requires: more storage, more efficient use, better seasonal management","Climate change has no effect on monsoons"], ans:2, exp:"Climate modelling for South Asia shows concerning trends. The Indian Summer Monsoon (ISM) is being weakened by: (1) Aerosol pollution reducing solar heating of land. (2) Arctic warming reducing land-sea temperature gradient that drives monsoon. Simultaneously, extreme precipitation events are increasing — short, intense rains that cause flooding rather than soil infiltration. For India's 600 million smallholder farmers who depend on monsoon timing and distribution, these changes are existential. The Himalayan glaciers — feeding 500 million people's rivers — are losing mass at accelerating rates." },
  { q:"Why is the Kaveri water dispute between Karnataka and Tamil Nadu so difficult to resolve?", opts:["It is purely a technical dispute","One state is entirely wrong","The Kaveri dispute involves: (1) Competing historical rights — both states have legitimate historical claims. (2) Economic development needs — Karnataka needs water for Bengaluru city and Mysuru agriculture; Tamil Nadu needs water for Cauvery delta paddy. (3) Uncertainty — rainfall varies year to year; how to share water in drought years? (4) Power politics — water release decisions become electoral issues in both states. (5) Legal complexity — multiple Supreme Court orders; implementation contested. The dispute shows that when water is scarce, allocation involves genuine trade-offs that technical solutions alone cannot resolve — requiring political negotiation and compromise that both states' politicians resist","Only Tamil Nadu is right"], ans:2, exp:"The Kaveri dispute is the paradigm case of India's interstate water conflicts. The river basin falls across Karnataka and Tamil Nadu (and partly Kerala and Puducherry). Karnataka built dams that Tamil Nadu argues reduce its water. Tamil Nadu argues it has prior rights based on colonial-era agreements. The Kaveri Tribunal's 2007 final award allocated water between states — but implementation remains contested, with periodic Supreme Court interventions. The dispute escalated to communal riots in 2016. There is no permanent resolution — only management, because rainfall variability means no fixed allocation can always be honoured." },
  { q:"How do wetlands function as natural water management infrastructure?", opts:["Wetlands waste water","Wetlands are useless for water management","Wetlands provide multiple water services: (1) WATER STORAGE: Absorb and store monsoon flood waters — releasing slowly. (2) GROUNDWATER RECHARGE: Allow water to percolate, recharging aquifers. (3) WATER PURIFICATION: Filter pollutants, break down organic waste. (4) FLOOD MITIGATION: Absorb excess water, reducing downstream floods. (5) DROUGHT MITIGATION: Release stored water during dry seasons. India has lost 70%+ of wetlands in 50 years — directly worsening floods and water scarcity. Loktak Lake (Manipur), Chilika Lake (Odisha), Sambhar Lake (Rajasthan) are remaining important wetlands facing severe degradation","Wetlands only matter for birds"], ans:2, exp:"Wetland loss is a major underappreciated driver of both floods and water scarcity. Bengaluru had 262 lakes in the 1800s — now has about 100, most highly polluted. The city floods severely during monsoon (because natural retention capacity is gone) and faces severe water shortage in summer. The lakes that remain — Ulsoor, Bellandur — are severely polluted with sewage and industrial waste. Restoring urban wetlands is increasingly recognised as essential infrastructure for climate adaptation — cheaper and more effective than conventional flood control infrastructure." },
  { q:"ASSERTION: India's water crisis is as much a governance problem as a supply problem.\nREASON: India receives sufficient rainfall to meet its water needs, but inadequate storage infrastructure, weak regulation of groundwater extraction, inefficient agricultural use, and inadequate wastewater treatment together create unnecessary scarcity.", opts:["Both A and R true; R explains why governance matters more than supply","Both true but unconnected","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"Both correct. India receives 4000 billion cubic metres of annual rainfall — theoretically sufficient for its needs. But: (1) Only ~1,100 bcm is utilised (lack of storage infrastructure). (2) 80% of water use is agriculture, with low efficiency. (3) Groundwater extraction is essentially unregulated — the world's highest groundwater extractor. (4) Only 30% of sewage is treated — contaminating remaining surface water. (5) Inter-state disputes reduce coordinated management. Each of these is a governance failure — solvable through better institutions, policies and enforcement. Supply is not the fundamental constraint; governance is." },
];

const ch3_hardMCQ = [
  { q:"ASSERTION: Large dams are neither universally good nor universally bad — their evaluation depends on context, implementation quality and governance of displacement.\nREASON: The World Commission on Dams found that while dams provided development benefits, they often failed to meet objectives, displaced millions without adequate rehabilitation, and caused irreversible environmental damage.", opts:["Both A and R true; R provides the empirical basis for the contextual evaluation","Both true but unconnected","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"Both correct. The WCD (2000) report is the most authoritative assessment of large dam impacts globally. Its findings: (1) ~40-80 million people displaced globally by large dams; most inadequately rehabilitated. (2) Economic returns frequently below projections; many dams financially unviable. (3) Environmental damage frequently severe and underestimated. (4) Some dams DID provide significant benefits. The contextual evaluation this demands: What are the alternatives? How will displacement be managed? What environmental mitigation is possible? This is more honest than either uncritical promotion or blanket opposition." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: A semi-arid district in Rajasthan faces declining groundwater levels, falling farm incomes and migration. The government proposes a new canal irrigation scheme. Community activists propose reviving traditional johads. Evaluate both options.", opts:["Canal irrigation is always better","Traditional methods are always better","Canal irrigation: Benefits — guaranteed water supply; can support intensified agriculture. Problems — capital intensive; changes crop patterns; if water allocation is in excess of sustainable extraction, same problem reproduced. Johads: Benefits — recharge groundwater locally; community-managed; culturally integrated; low-cost. Problems — depends on local rainfall; lower water volumes than canals. Best approach: Johads for groundwater recharge and resilience + selective canal irrigation for supplemental supply + crop diversification away from water-intensive crops. The two approaches are complementary if water budgets are respected","Neither approach would work"], ans:2, exp:"This reflects real Rajasthan experience. The Alwar district (Rajendra Singh's work) showed johad revival can transform water-scarce areas by recharging groundwater — allowing farmers to grow crops with tube wells fed by recharged aquifers rather than depleted fossil groundwater. But johads alone may not provide enough water for intensive agriculture. Canal irrigation is reliable but can encourage unsustainable cropping patterns. The optimal solution integrates: traditional water harvesting for groundwater recharge + supplemental surface water for high-value crops + crop diversification to reduce water demand." },
  { q:"EXTRACT-BASED: 'The right to water is increasingly recognised as a human right — yet water is increasingly commodified as a market good.' What is the tension between these two perspectives and how should it be resolved?", opts:["Water is purely a market good","Water is purely a public good","True tension: Human rights perspective — water is essential for life; no one should be denied it for inability to pay; it should be publicly provided. Market perspective — water as a commodity allows pricing that discourages waste and funds infrastructure. Resolution: A rights-based approach to BASIC water (sufficient for drinking, cooking, sanitation) as a guaranteed public provision; market pricing for non-essential or excessive use. This 'rising block tariff' model (low price for basic needs, higher for excess) combines rights and efficiency. Privatisation of basic water supply (as attempted in Bolivia, India) has often failed — raising prices without improving service","All water should be free"], ans:2, exp:"The human right to water was recognised by the UN General Assembly in 2010. But many countries (including India) have experimented with water privatisation, often with poor results for low-income communities (price increases) without service improvements. The rising block tariff model (used in some Indian cities) is considered the best compromise: (1) First 50 litres per person per day free or subsidised. (2) Consumption above that charged at increasing rates. (3) Revenue funds infrastructure maintenance. This protects the right to basic water while creating efficiency incentives for higher consumption." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: How does the Farakka Barrage dispute between India and Bangladesh illustrate the geopolitical dimensions of transboundary water management?", opts:["Farakka has no international implications","Bangladesh fully accepts India's use of Ganga water","India built Farakka Barrage (1975) to increase Hooghly River flow to prevent Kolkata port silting. Bangladesh argues this reduces Ganga flow into Bangladesh — harming its agriculture, fisheries and the Sundarbans. Issues: (1) Lower riparian vs upper riparian rights — Bangladesh argues India cannot reduce historically shared river flow. (2) Environmental impact — reduced freshwater flow increases salinity in Bangladesh's Ganga delta, threatening agriculture and Sundarbans mangroves. (3) Governance — India-Bangladesh Ganga Water Sharing Treaty (1996, renewed 2026) attempts to allocate water, but implementation is disputed. This shows that shared rivers require bilateral or multilateral governance frameworks — unilateral upstream actions cause downstream harm","India has complete rights over all Ganga water"], ans:2, exp:"The Farakka dispute is the most important transboundary water conflict in South Asia. The Ganga flows from India into Bangladesh where it becomes the Padma. Farakka diverts 40,000+ cusecs during dry season into the Hooghly — significantly reducing Padma flow. Bangladesh has documented: (1) Reduced groundwater recharge in the delta. (2) Increased salinity affecting 30 million people's agriculture. (3) Damage to the Sundarbans from salinity intrusion. The 1996 Treaty provides a framework but satisfaction with implementation varies. The case shows that rivers are geopolitical objects — dams built for national purposes have international consequences that require diplomatic management." },
  { q:"ASSERTION: Integrated Water Resource Management (IWRM) is a more effective approach to water management than sector-specific management.\nREASON: Managing water as a unified system — across agriculture, industry, domestic use, environment, and transboundary considerations — prevents the contradictions and inefficiencies that arise when each sector manages its water independently.", opts:["Both A and R true; R explains why integrated management is superior","Both true but unconnected","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"Both correct. India's water management fragmentation: Ministry of Agriculture handles irrigation; Ministry of Jal Shakti handles rivers; states control groundwater; different agencies handle industrial water; environment ministry handles river pollution. Result: irrigation ministry digs canals that salinate land; environment ministry promotes groundwater recharge while agriculture ministry encourages groundwater extraction for paddy. IWRM — treating water across sectors as a unified resource — prevents these contradictions. India's National Water Policy (2012) calls for IWRM but institutional fragmentation makes implementation difficult." },
  { q:"How does the depletion of the Himalayan glaciers pose a long-term threat to Indian water security that current water management frameworks are not adequately addressing?", opts:["Himalayan glacier retreat will increase water availability","Glacier retreat has no effect on Indian rivers","Himalayan glaciers feed 8 major river systems serving 500+ million people. Short-term: increased melt → more river flow. Medium term (2050-2100): glaciers shrink → reduced dry season flow when demand is highest. Long-term risk: rivers that currently have year-round flow from glacial melt will become seasonal. Current frameworks fail because: (1) Water plans use historical hydrology — don't account for changing glacier contribution. (2) Infrastructure (dams) designed for past flows may be mismatched to future regimes. (3) No serious national adaptation planning for post-glacier river systems. (4) Agricultural settlement patterns (irrigation-dependent crops) assume stable river flows","Glaciers only affect Tibet"], ans:2, exp:"The glacial retreat threat is serious and inadequately planned for. The Himalayas contain 9,575 glaciers covering 40,000 sq km — the largest glacial mass outside the poles. Average retreat rate has doubled since the 1970s. For rivers like the Indus (60% glacial contribution in summer), the loss of glacial water would be catastrophic for Pakistan and northwest India. For the Ganga-Brahmaputra system, glacial contribution is lower (20-30%) but still significant. India's dam planning continues to use historical hydrology rather than projecting glacier retreat trajectories — a serious planning failure." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: A pharmaceutical company proposes a factory near a river that would create 10,000 jobs but discharge partially treated effluents. How should this decision be made using an integrated water management framework?", opts:["Jobs always take precedence","The factory should never be allowed","An integrated framework requires: (1) Environmental Impact Assessment quantifying effluent load and impacts on river ecology and downstream users. (2) Comparison with alternative locations with less sensitive water resources. (3) Zero liquid discharge technology as a condition — technically feasible for pharmaceutical industry. (4) Economic analysis including cost of downstream water treatment for agricultural/domestic users affected. (5) Community consultation with downstream water users. (6) Long-term monitoring with closure requirements if standards are violated. The choice between jobs and environment is often false — proper technology can achieve both. The question is whether enforcement mechanisms are trusted to work","Economics always outweighs environment"], ans:2, exp:"This reflects the real challenge of industrial water management in India. The Ganges pollution problem is substantially caused by industries (particularly tanneries in Kanpur, textile mills in Surat) that discharge partially treated or untreated effluents because: (1) Treatment is expensive. (2) Enforcement is weak. (3) Political economy — industries provide jobs and tax revenue. Integrated water management would require: (1) Real-time monitoring of discharge. (2) Meaningful penalties for violations. (3) Technology standards (zero liquid discharge is achievable). (4) True cost accounting including downstream impacts. The pharmaceutical industry is technically capable of zero discharge — the question is governance and enforcement." },
  { q:"EXTRACT: 'Water conflict between nations is the oil conflict of the 21st century.' Evaluate this prediction.", opts:["Water conflicts will not occur","Oil conflicts are more important than water","The prediction has significant validity: (1) Unlike oil, water has no substitute for most uses. (2) Climate change is increasing water stress globally. (3) Transboundary rivers serve multiple nations with competing needs (Mekong, Nile, Indus, Brahmaputra). (4) Groundwater depletion is making countries dependent on finite reserves. (5) Economic development is increasing per-capita water demand. Counter-arguments: (1) Water is local — unlike oil, cannot easily be transported to substitute for local shortages. (2) Most water conflicts are intranational (inter-state) rather than international. (3) Water cooperation is more common than conflict — shared rivers usually produce more cooperation than war. The most accurate prediction: water will increasingly generate TENSION and competition, but unlike oil, is more likely to produce cooperative frameworks than military conflict","Water is abundant globally"], ans:2, exp:"The water-conflict prediction is partly right but overstated. Since 1948, there have been fewer than 40 armed conflicts over water globally, while there have been over 200 water cooperation agreements. Most water 'conflicts' are legal-diplomatic (like Kaveri or Farakka) rather than military. However: Pakistan-India tensions over Indus Waters Treaty (2016 India threatened review after Uri attack); Ethiopia-Egypt tension over Grand Ethiopian Renaissance Dam on Nile; China's dam construction on Mekong headwaters creating tension with SE Asian nations. The future trajectory depends on climate change intensity and governance quality — with worse climate outcomes and weaker governance, armed conflict becomes more likely." },
  { q:"ASSERTION: India's Green Revolution has created a water management crisis that threatens long-term food security.\nREASON: Green Revolution technologies (high-yielding varieties, chemical inputs, tube well irrigation) dramatically increased yields but created dependence on groundwater that is now being depleted at unsustainable rates in key food-producing states.", opts:["Both A and R true; R correctly identifies the mechanism by which Green Revolution creates water crisis","Both true but unconnected","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"Both correct. The Green Revolution is simultaneously India's greatest development achievement and a major sustainability problem. In Punjab and Haryana: wheat and rice yields increased 5-10 fold, making India food self-sufficient. But the cost: (1) Paddy (not a traditional Punjab crop) requires flooding — enormous water input. (2) Tube well irrigation with subsidised electricity created incentive to extract unlimited groundwater. (3) Water table in central Punjab falls 0.5-1m annually. (4) Some areas now have no recoverable groundwater. The crisis: if Punjab's groundwater fails, India's food security fails. The solution (diversifying crops, pricing water, drip irrigation) is technically clear but politically very difficult — farmers' incomes depend on the current system." },
  { q:"How does water governance in India reflect the broader challenges of decentralised vs centralised management in federal systems?", opts:["Water should only be centrally managed","Water should only be locally managed","Water governance in India spans: (1) Central government — river development, interstate disputes, national policy. (2) State governments — irrigation, groundwater regulation, water supply. (3) Local bodies — Panchayats, municipalities — service delivery. (4) Community institutions — traditional water management. The federal tension: states resist central interference in their water (water is a State subject under Constitution's 7th Schedule). But interstate disputes require central arbitration. Groundwater is legally a property of landowners — no national groundwater regulation. The result: each level manages its jurisdiction without coordination — canal irrigation undermines groundwater; state irrigation schemes conflict with interstate obligations; local bodies lack resources for water supply infrastructure. Effective water governance requires multilevel coordination that India's institutions don't currently achieve","Federal systems cannot manage water"], ans:2, exp:"India's Constitution's 7th Schedule places water in the State List — meaning states have primary jurisdiction. This creates problems: (1) States develop their rivers maximally without considering downstream states. (2) Groundwater is legally treated as belonging to land — anyone can pump whatever they want. (3) No national groundwater law exists. (4) Interstate river disputes drag through tribunals for decades. The National Water Policy calls for integrated management but has no legal force over states. Effective water governance would require: either a constitutional amendment (politically nearly impossible) or a cooperative federalism framework for water — which requires all states and the centre to agree on sharing costs and benefits." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: Describe how Chennai's urban water crisis of 2019 (when four major reservoirs ran dry) illustrates the intersection of climate, governance, and infrastructure failures.", opts:["The crisis was purely a drought","The crisis was only about politics","Chennai 2019 water crisis involved multiple simultaneous failures: (1) Climate: 2018 northeast monsoon was deficient. (2) Infrastructure: heavy dependence on four reservoirs with insufficient backup; limited groundwater alternatives; no significant desalination; over-dependence on monsoon without storage diversification. (3) Governance: 94% of Chennai's wetlands lost to urbanisation — reducing water retention capacity. Unregulated groundwater extraction. No mandatory rainwater harvesting enforcement for decades. Delayed investment in desalination. (4) Social: extreme inequality — rich areas had water trucked in; poor areas went without. The crisis showed that urban water security requires: diversified sources, wetland protection, mandatory rainwater harvesting, groundwater regulation, and governance that prioritises water infrastructure","All Indian cities face identical problems"], ans:2, exp:"Chennai 2019 was a preventable crisis that represents a failure mode increasingly common in Indian cities. The specific factors: (1) 94% of Chennai's original wetlands lost to real estate development — eliminated natural storage and recharge. (2) All four major reservoirs dependent on the same northeast monsoon — no source diversification. (3) Rainwater harvesting made mandatory (2003) but enforcement lapsed. (4) No meaningful desalination capacity until crisis hit. (5) Groundwater extraction unregulated. The immediate aftermath: desalination plants built, rainwater harvesting reinvigorated. But without systematic changes to how urban land use is governed (protecting wetlands, mandatory rainwater harvesting, groundwater regulation), the next deficit monsoon will produce a similar crisis." },
];

const ch5_pyqs = [
  { title:"PYQ 2023", question:"What is a mineral? Explain its characteristics.", answer:"A mineral is a naturally occurring inorganic substance with a definite chemical composition and an internal crystal structure. Minerals are unevenly distributed, finite in nature, and formed by geological processes over long periods of time.", year:2023, marks:3, difficulty:"easy" },
  { title:"PYQ 2023", question:"Classify minerals on the basis of composition.", answer:"Minerals are classified into metallic and non-metallic minerals. Metallic minerals include ferrous minerals like iron ore and manganese, and non-ferrous minerals like copper and bauxite. Non-metallic minerals include mica, limestone, and gypsum.", year:2023, marks:3, difficulty:"easy" },
  { title:"PYQ 2022", question:"Explain the occurrence of minerals in igneous and metamorphic rocks.", answer:"In igneous and metamorphic rocks, minerals occur in cracks, faults, fractures and joints. These are called veins and lodes. Smaller deposits are veins and larger ones are lodes, such as tin, copper, zinc and lead.", year:2022, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2022", question:"Why is conservation of minerals necessary?", answer:"Minerals are non-renewable and take millions of years to form. Their overuse leads to exhaustion of reserves. Conservation is necessary through judicious use, recycling, efficient technologies and substitution of scarce minerals.", year:2022, marks:3, difficulty:"easy" },
  { title:"PYQ 2021", question:"Describe the major iron ore belts of India.", answer:"The major iron ore belts of India are Odisha-Jharkhand belt, Durg-Bastar-Chandrapur belt, Bellary-Chitradurga-Chikmagalur-Tumakuru belt, and Maharashtra-Goa belt. These regions contain major hematite and magnetite reserves.", year:2021, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2021", question:"What are placer deposits?", answer:"Placer deposits are mineral deposits found in sands of valley floors, river beds, and ocean beaches. They are formed by the action of water and usually contain minerals like gold, silver, tin and platinum.", year:2021, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2020", question:"Explain the distribution of bauxite in India.", answer:"Bauxite is found in Odisha, Gujarat, Jharkhand, Maharashtra, Chhattisgarh, Tamil Nadu and Madhya Pradesh. Odisha is the largest producer. It is the main ore of aluminium.", year:2020, marks:3, difficulty:"easy" },
  { title:"PYQ 2020", question:"What are the uses of mica?", answer:"Mica is used in electrical and electronic industries because it is a good insulator. It is also used in paints, cosmetics, rubber and aerospace equipment.", year:2020, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2019", question:"What is mineral conservation?", answer:"Mineral conservation means using minerals carefully and efficiently, reducing wastage, recycling metals, and adopting technologies that make better use of limited mineral resources.", year:2019, marks:3, difficulty:"easy" },
  { title:"PYQ 2019", question:"Explain the importance of petroleum.", answer:"Petroleum is an important energy resource and a raw material for the petrochemical industry. It is used in transport, industry, power generation, lubricants, plastics, fertilizers and synthetic fibres.", year:2019, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2023", question:"Why is coal called a non-renewable source of energy?", answer:"Coal takes millions of years to form from buried plant matter under heat and pressure. Since it cannot be replaced within a human time scale, it is a non-renewable source of energy.", year:2023, marks:1, difficulty:"easy" },
  { title:"PYQ 2022", question:"What is thermal power?", answer:"Thermal power is electricity generated by burning coal, petroleum or natural gas in thermal power plants.", year:2022, marks:1, difficulty:"easy" },
  { title:"PYQ 2021", question:"What is tidal energy?", answer:"Tidal energy is energy generated from the rise and fall of ocean tides by using tidal power plants.", year:2021, marks:1, difficulty:"easy" },
  { title:"PYQ 2020", question:"Name two non-conventional sources of energy.", answer:"Solar energy and wind energy are two non-conventional sources of energy.", year:2020, marks:1, difficulty:"easy" },
  { title:"PYQ 2019", question:"What is biogas?", answer:"Biogas is a fuel produced by the decomposition of animal and plant waste in the absence of oxygen. It is mainly used for cooking and lighting.", year:2019, marks:1, difficulty:"easy" }
];

